{"parentUuid":"a6bce7d4-9959-4a2a-b220-65e5efaf0085","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"bash \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/hooks/run-with-flags-shell.sh\" \"post:observe\" \"skills/continuous-learning-v2/hooks/observe.sh\" \"standard,strict\""},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01KtUqbKvF4PnbyWWAZyMXxu","toolUseID":"toolu_01KtUqbKvF4PnbyWWAZyMXxu","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:20:26.364Z","uuid":"841e4b6d-291a-4a46-bafe-dafe581bdb50","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"841e4b6d-291a-4a46-bafe-dafe581bdb50","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01KtUqbKvF4PnbyWWAZyMXxu","toolUseID":"toolu_01KtUqbKvF4PnbyWWAZyMXxu","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:20:26.364Z","uuid":"e6028681-00c4-4450-a0e0-077874239470","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"c5fb7a6c-d5d9-4412-a678-c17f0f1c8443","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"3cfdca64-d5a0-407a-b98d-81d58c820453","agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KtUqbKvF4PnbyWWAZyMXxu","type":"tool_result","content":"<persisted-output>\nOutput too large (76KB). Full output saved to: /Users/dhyana/.claude/projects/-Users-dhyana/2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75/tool-results/toolu_01KtUqbKvF4PnbyWWAZyMXxu.txt\n\nPreview (first 2KB):\n     1→# Welfare-Tons: Mathematical Specification\n     2→\n     3→## The North Star Metric for Jagat Kalyan\n     4→\n     5→**Version**: 2.0\n     6→**Date**: 2026-03-11\n     7→**Author**: John \"Dhyana\" Shrader, with analytical support from Claude\n     8→**Status**: Draft specification -- ready for peer review and pilot calibration\n     9→**Revision note**: v2.0 restructures the formula to a flat 6-factor multiplicative architecture. v1.0 folded permanence into the carbon component and nested employment, agency, and other social indicators inside a composite $S$ multiplier. v2.0 promotes each dimension to a top-level factor: $W = C \\times E \\times A \\times B \\times V \\times P$. The motivation: zero in any dimension yields zero welfare-tons, with no possibility of hiding a deficit inside a composite.\n    10→\n    11→---\n    12→\n    13→## 0. Design Principles\n    14→\n    15→1. **Multiplicative, not additive.** Following the Jain principle *Parasparopagraho Jivanam* (souls render service to one another), welfare is indivisible. Zero in any dimension yields zero welfare-tons. You cannot trade ecological harm for social benefit. You cannot trade community displacement for carbon tonnage.\n    16→\n    17→2. **Zero kills the product.** If a project sequesters carbon but creates no jobs ($E = 0$), the welfare-tons are zero. If a project employs workers but the community never consented ($A = 0$), the welfare-tons are zero. This is the central enforcement mechanism against greenwashing: every dimension must be positive.\n    18→\n    19→3. **Conservative by default.** When data is missing or uncertain, sub-indicators default to their floor value. The metric rewards transparency and measurement, not optimistic self-reporting.\n    20→\n...\n</persisted-output>"}]},"uuid":"b9761d4e-da70-4b60-bbca-ff355609fb18","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:20:26.364Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"c5fb7a6c-d5d9-4412-a678-c17f0f1c8443","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"b9761d4e-da70-4b60-bbca-ff355609fb18","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"bash \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/hooks/run-with-flags-shell.sh\" \"post:observe\" \"skills/continuous-learning-v2/hooks/observe.sh\" \"standard,strict\""},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01QjtU3835rvSpe4wjByqrPD","toolUseID":"toolu_01QjtU3835rvSpe4wjByqrPD","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:20:26.751Z","uuid":"97cc08c0-7ae2-4601-822a-ee95f81e3ff1","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"97cc08c0-7ae2-4601-822a-ee95f81e3ff1","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01QjtU3835rvSpe4wjByqrPD","toolUseID":"toolu_01QjtU3835rvSpe4wjByqrPD","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:20:26.751Z","uuid":"d29bee9e-441f-4c65-9446-0fdde6d903a5","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"dde6b1c7-5dbe-4635-a036-66549c7df0e0","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"3cfdca64-d5a0-407a-b98d-81d58c820453","agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QjtU3835rvSpe4wjByqrPD","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Carbon Attribution Feasibility Study\n     2→\n     3→**Jagat Kalyan: Per-Inference Carbon Attribution for AI-Coordinated Ecological Restoration**\n     4→\n     5→Version 1.0 | March 2026\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Executive Summary\n    10→\n    11→Jagat Kalyan's core innovation is **per-inference carbon attribution** -- tagging every AI API call with its marginal ecological cost, then routing offset demand into verified ecological restoration. This document assesses the technical feasibility, market opportunity, and implementation pathway for this approach.\n    12→\n    13→**Bottom line**: Per-inference carbon attribution is feasible today at the estimation level (within +/-40% accuracy), achievable at higher precision within 6 months using real-time grid data and open-source tooling, and could reach provider-verified accuracy within 2 years contingent on industry partnerships. The voluntary carbon market is growing rapidly enough (CAGR 35-50%) to absorb AI-offset demand, and emerging standards (ISO/IEC 21031, GSF SCI for AI) provide regulatory tailwinds.\n    14→\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→## 1. Per-Inference Energy Consumption\n    18→\n    19→### 1.1 Known Energy Benchmarks\n    20→\n    21→The energy cost of a single AI inference varies by model, prompt length, output length, and hardware. Published and estimated benchmarks as of early 2026:\n    22→\n    23→| Model | Energy per Query (Wh) | Source / Basis |\n    24→|-------|----------------------|----------------|\n    25→| Google Search (baseline) | ~0.30 | Google disclosures |\n    26→| Google Gemini (text) | ~0.24 | Google environmental report |\n    27→| ChatGPT (GPT-4o, short) | ~0.34-0.42 | OpenAI disclosures; Epoch AI analysis |\n    28→| ChatGPT (GPT-4o, typical) | ~0.42 | Epoch AI (Feb 2025 revision) |\n    29→| Claude 3 Haiku | ~0.22 | Public benchmarks (estimated) |\n    30→| Claude 3.7 Sonnet | ~0.5-1.5 | Estimated range; no official disclosure |\n    31→| Claude 3 Opus (~400 tokens) | ~4.05 | Public benchmarks (estimated) |\n    32→| Reasoning models (o1, R1) | ~10-20 | 30-50x base model; extended chain-of-thought |\n    33→\n    34→**Key observations:**\n    35→\n    36→- There is roughly a 100x range between the cheapest inference (small model, short query) and the most expensive (large reasoning model, long output).\n    37→- Reasoning models (OpenAI o1, DeepSeek R1) consume 30-50x more energy than standard models because they generate extensive internal reasoning chains before producing output.\n    38→- Anthropic does not publicly disclose per-inference energy figures for Claude. Estimates for Claude 3.7 Sonnet range from 0.5 to 1.5 Wh depending on output length. The 0.95 Wh figure cited in some analyses is a reasonable midpoint estimate for a typical ~500-token exchange.\n    39→- All figures are pre-PUE (facility overhead not included).\n    40→\n    41→### 1.2 Variance Factors\n    42→\n    43→Energy per inference is not a fixed number. It varies along several dimensions:\n    44→\n    45→**Model size**: Roughly proportional to parameter count for autoregressive generation. A 70B model uses approximately 10x the compute of a 7B model per token. Mixture-of-experts architectures (Mixtral, GPT-4) activate only a subset of parameters, reducing this proportionality.\n    46→\n    47→**Prompt length (input tokens)**: The prefill phase processes all input tokens in parallel. Energy scales roughly linearly with prompt length but is amortized across the full response. A 10,000-token prompt costs more than a 100-token prompt, but not 100x more, because the generation phase dominates for long outputs.\n    48→\n    49→**Output length (generated tokens)**: The primary energy driver. Each output token requires a full forward pass through the model. A 2,000-token response costs roughly 10x a 200-token response in generation energy.\n    50→\n    51→**Hardware**: NVIDIA H100 GPUs are roughly 2-3x more energy-efficient per FLOP than A100s. Google TPUv5 shows similar generational improvements. Older hardware in non-hyperscaler data centers may be 5-10x less efficient than cutting-edge chips.\n    52→\n    53→**Batch size and utilization**: High-throughput serving (batched inference) amortizes fixed costs. A GPU running at 90% utilization is far more energy-efficient per inference than one at 20%. This is a major source of variance between providers.\n    54→\n    55→### 1.3 Data Center PUE (Power Usage Effectiveness)\n    56→\n    57→PUE measures total facility energy divided by IT equipment energy. A PUE of 1.2 means 20% overhead for cooling, networking, lighting, and other infrastructure.\n    58→\n    59→| Operator | PUE (2025) | Notes |\n    60→|----------|-----------|-------|\n    61→| Google | 1.09 | Industry-leading; trailing 12-month average |\n    62→| AWS | 1.15 | Global average; best site 1.04 (Europe) |\n    63→| Microsoft Azure | 1.11-1.35 | Range across facilities; best in Wyoming |\n    64→| Industry average | 1.54 | Uptime Institute 2025 survey |\n    65→| Enterprise (non-hyperscale) | 1.5-1.8 | Older facilities |\n    66→\n    67→**Implication for attribution**: The PUE multiplier adds 9-80% to raw compute energy depending on the data center. For hyperscaler-hosted models (Claude, GPT, Gemini), a PUE of 1.1-1.2 is appropriate. For self-hosted or enterprise deployments, 1.4-1.8 is more realistic.\n    68→\n    69→### 1.4 Marginal vs. Average Cost\n    70→\n    71→The fundamental measurement challenge: does an additional inference consume marginal energy (the cost of one more query on an already-running GPU) or average energy (total facility energy / total queries)?\n    72→\n    73→- **Marginal cost** is lower because GPUs are already powered on and partially utilized. Adding one query to a batch barely changes total power draw.\n    74→- **Average cost** captures the proportional share of all overhead, including idle time between queries, redundant capacity, and cooling.\n    75→- **For attribution purposes**, average cost is more appropriate because it reflects the true resource consumption allocated to each inference. Marginal cost would undercount by ignoring shared infrastructure.\n    76→\n    77→EcoLogits and similar tools use average cost estimation, which is the correct approach for carbon attribution.\n    78→\n    79→---\n    80→\n    81→## 2. Carbon Intensity Conversion\n    82→\n    83→### 2.1 From Wh to gCO2\n    84→\n    85→The conversion is straightforward in principle:\n    86→\n    87→```\n    88→gCO2 per inference = (Wh per inference) x PUE x (gCO2/kWh grid intensity) / 1000\n    89→```\n    90→\n    91→**Worked example** (ChatGPT query, US average grid):\n    92→```\n    93→0.42 Wh x 1.15 PUE x 390 gCO2/kWh / 1000 = 0.188 gCO2 per query\n    94→```\n    95→\n    96→**Worked example** (Claude 3 Opus, Sweden hydro grid):\n    97→```\n    98→4.05 Wh x 1.10 PUE x 16 gCO2/kWh / 1000 = 0.071 gCO2 per query\n    99→```\n   100→\n   101→The same model can produce a 10-50x difference in carbon intensity depending on where the data center is located.\n   102→\n   103→### 2.2 Grid Carbon Intensity by Region\n   104→\n   105→Grid carbon intensity varies dramatically by geography and energy mix:\n   106→\n   107→| Region | gCO2/kWh | Primary Mix |\n   108→|--------|----------|-------------|\n   109→| Sweden | 16 | 98% hydro/nuclear |\n   110→| France | 56 | 70% nuclear |\n   111→| UK (2025 avg) | 129 | Mixed; declining rapidly |\n   112→| EU average | ~230 | Varies widely by country |\n   113→| US average | ~390 | Mixed; regional variation 200-800 |\n   114→| US (PJM/coal-heavy) | ~600-800 | Coal + gas |\n   115→| US (California) | ~200-250 | High solar/wind |\n   116→| China (national avg) | ~530 | Coal-dominant |\n   117→| India | ~630 | Coal-dominant |\n   118→| Global average (2024) | ~445 | Declining at ~3.7%/year |\n   119→\n   120→**Real-time APIs** make dynamic attribution possible:\n   121→- **WattTime** API: 5-minute marginal emissions data for most US and European grids.\n   122→- **ElectricityMaps** API: Real-time and forecasted carbon intensity for 200+ zones globally.\n   123→- **UK Carbon Intensity API** (National Grid ESO): 30-minute granularity, free.\n   124→\n   125→### 2.3 Time-of-Day Variation\n   126→\n   127→Grid carbon intensity is not static. It varies by:\n   128→\n   129→- **Hour of day**: Solar-heavy grids are cleaner midday; wind varies unpredictably.\n   130→- **Season**: Heating demand in winter increases fossil fuel usage in many grids.\n   131→- **Demand level**: Peak demand often triggers dirtier peaker plants (gas turbines).\n   132→\n   133→A query made at 2 PM in California (abundant solar) might have half the carbon intensity of the same query at 10 PM. Real-time grid data enables this level of attribution precision.\n   134→\n   135→### 2.4 Scope 1/2/3 Emissions\n   136→\n   137→Carbon accounting follows the Greenhouse Gas Protocol's scope framework. For AI inference:\n   138→\n   139→| Scope | What It Covers | % of Total | Data Availability |\n   140→|-------|---------------|-----------|-------------------|\n   141→| Scope 1 | Direct on-site emissions (diesel generators, refrigerants) | 0.2-0.5% | Low; provider-specific |\n   142→| Scope 2 | Purchased electricity for operations | 31-61% | Medium; grid data + PUE |\n   143→| Scope 3 | Embodied carbon (GPU manufacturing, supply chain, end-of-life) | 38-69% | Very low; requires LCA data |\n   144→\n   145→**Critical insight**: Scope 3 (embodied carbon) can be the largest contributor, especially for data centers on clean grids. A GPU's lifecycle emissions from silicon mining, fab fabrication, global logistics, and disposal are substantial. Estimates suggest an NVIDIA H100's embodied carbon is roughly 150-200 kgCO2, amortized over its operational lifetime (typically 3-5 years).\n   146→\n   147→**Practical implication for Jagat Kalyan**: MVP should focus on Scope 2 (electricity-based), which is measurable today. Scope 3 requires hardware-specific LCA data that is not publicly available at the component level. Full Scope 1/2/3 attribution is a Phase 4 goal.\n   148→\n   149→---\n   150→\n   151→## 3. Existing Tools and Standards\n   152→\n   153→### 3.1 EcoLogits\n   154→\n   155→**What it is**: A Python library that wraps LLM API calls and estimates the environmental footprint of each inference. Published in the Journal of Open Source Software (JOSS).\n   156→\n   157→**How it works**:\n   158→1. Intercepts API calls to supported providers (OpenAI, Anthropic, Google, Mistral, Cohere, Hugging Face).\n   159→2. Monitors observable parameters (input/output token counts, model name).\n   160→3. Estimates GPU power consumption using regression models incorporating accelerator type, CPU, and DRAM specifications.\n   161→4. Multiplies by PUE and regional carbon intensity to produce per-query emissions.\n   162→\n   163→**Accuracy**: Uses the ML.ENERGY Leaderboard as its energy benchmark (updated in 2025 to replace the LLM-Perf Leaderboard). Estimated accuracy is within +/-40% based on external validation studies.\n   164→\n   165→**Relevance to Jagat Kalyan**: EcoLogits is the most directly applicable existing tool. It already does what Jagat Kalyan's Phase 1 needs: wrapping API calls with carbon estimates. The question is whether its accuracy and coverage are sufficient, or whether a custom layer is needed.\n   166→\n   167→### 3.2 ISO/IEC 21031:2024 -- Software Carbon Intensity (SCI)\n   168→\n   169→Published March 2024 as the first international standard for software carbon intensity. Developed by the Green Software Foundation and adopted by ISO/IEC JTC 1.\n   170→\n   171→**The SCI formula**:\n   172→```\n   173→SCI = ((E x I) + M) per R\n   174→```\n   175→Where:\n   176→- **E** = Energy consumed by the software system\n   177→- **I** = Location-based marginal carbon emissions of the grid\n   178→- **M** = Embodied emissions of hardware\n   179→- **R** = Functional unit (per request, per user, per transaction)\n   180→\n   181→**Relevance**: SCI provides the normative framework for Jagat Kalyan's attribution methodology. Aligning with ISO/IEC 21031 gives the system credibility with enterprise customers and regulators. The \"per R\" functional unit maps directly to \"per inference.\"\n   182→\n   183→### 3.3 GSF SCI for AI\n   184→\n   185→The Green Software Foundation ratified the **SCI for AI** specification in 2025-2026, extending the base SCI standard specifically for AI systems. It covers:\n   186→\n   187→- Classical ML, computer vision, NLP, generative AI, and agentic systems.\n   188→- Functional units: tokens (for language models), inferences (for classifiers), FLOPs (for training).\n   189→- Two measurement boundaries: a **provider score** (covering model development, training, deployment) and a **consumer score** (covering inference usage).\n   190→\n   191→**2026 focus**: GSF will publish practical implementation guidance for production AI systems. This timing aligns well with Jagat Kalyan's Phase 2-3 roadmap.\n   192→\n   193→### 3.4 CodeCarbon\n   194→\n   195→An open-source Python package developed by Mila, BCG GAMMA, Haverford College, and Comet.ml. Measures hardware electricity consumption (GPU + CPU + RAM) at fixed intervals and applies regional carbon intensity.\n   196→\n   197→**Strengths**: Direct hardware measurement (not estimation). Fine-grained per-device tracking. Active community.\n   198→\n   199→**Limitations**: Requires local hardware access -- works for self-hosted models but not for API-based inference. External validation shows estimation errors of up to 40%. Best suited as a ground-truth calibration tool rather than a production attribution system.\n   200→\n   201→### 3.5 Cloud Provider Sustainability Dashboards\n   202→\n   203→| Provider | Tool | Granularity | API Access | Scopes |\n   204→|----------|------|-------------|------------|--------|\n   205→| AWS | Customer Carbon Footprint Tool (CCFT) | Quarterly, by service/region | No public API | 1, 2, 3 |\n   206→| Google Cloud | Carbon Footprint Dashboard | Monthly, by project/region/product | BigQuery export | 1, 2, 3 (location + market-based) |\n   207→| Microsoft Azure | Emissions Impact Dashboard + Carbon Optimization | Monthly, via Power BI / Fabric | Preview API | 1, 2, 3 |\n   208→\n   209→**Key gap**: None of these tools provide per-inference granularity. They report aggregate emissions at the service or project level. For per-inference attribution, Jagat Kalyan must build its own estimation layer.\n   210→\n   211→### 3.6 Other Notable Tools\n   212→\n   213→- **ML CO2 Impact Calculator** (mlco2.github.io): Simple web calculator for training runs. Not suitable for inference.\n   214→- **Climatiq API**: Carbon emission factors database with API access. Useful for conversion factors.\n   215→- **Cloud Carbon Footprint** (Thoughtworks): Open-source multi-cloud carbon estimator. Aggregate level, not per-inference.\n   216→- **Gravity Climate**: Developing AI-specific emissions accounting methodology. Worth monitoring.\n   217→\n   218→---\n   219→\n   220→## 4. Market Sizing\n   221→\n   222→### 4.1 Voluntary Carbon Market\n   223→\n   224→The voluntary carbon market (VCM) is the target market for AI-driven offset demand. Projections vary widely:\n   225→\n   226→| Source | 2026 Estimate | 2030 Estimate |\n   227→|--------|--------------|--------------|\n   228→| Mordor Intelligence | $23.8B | $120.5B |\n   229→| Grand View Research | -- | $24.0B |\n   230→| McKinsey | -- | $5B-$50B+ |\n   231→| MSCI | -- | $7B-$35B |\n   232→| Roots Analysis | $1.7B | -- |\n   233→\n   234→The wide spread reflects genuine uncertainty about corporate demand, regulatory drivers, and credit quality standards. The market contracted in 2023-2024 due to quality concerns (Verra scandal, integrity audits) but is recovering as Article 6.4 of the Paris Agreement creates a compliance pathway for voluntary credits.\n   235→\n   236→**Conservative working estimate**: $10-30B by 2030, growing at 35-50% CAGR.\n   237→\n   238→### 4.2 AI Inference Market\n   239→\n   240→The AI inference market provides the demand-side basis:\n   241→\n   242→| Source | 2025 | 2030 | CAGR |\n   243→|--------|------|------|------|\n   244→| MarketsandMarkets | $106B | $255B | 19.2% |\n   245→| Grand View Research | $97B | $254B | 17.5% |\n   246→| Fortune Business Insights | $104B | $255B | 13.7% |\n   247→\n   248→**Energy projection**: All generative AI queries are estimated to consume 15 TWh in 2025 and 347 TWh by 2030 (Epoch AI). At a global average of ~400 gCO2/kWh, this implies:\n   249→\n   250→```\n   251→2025: 15 TWh x 400 gCO2/kWh = 6 MtCO2\n   252→2030: 347 TWh x 350 gCO2/kWh = 121 MtCO2 (assuming grid decarbonization)\n   253→```\n   254→\n   255→### 4.3 TAM/SAM/SOM for Per-Inference Carbon Attribution\n   256→\n   257→**Total Addressable Market (TAM)**: The carbon cost of all AI inference globally.\n   258→- 2025: ~6 MtCO2 x $10-50/tonne (VCM price range) = $60M-$300M\n   259→- 2030: ~121 MtCO2 x $20-100/tonne (projected VCM price) = $2.4B-$12.1B\n   260→\n   261→**Serviceable Addressable Market (SAM)**: AI inference from companies with carbon commitments, using API-based models where per-inference attribution is technically feasible.\n   262→- Estimate 30-40% of inference is API-based (vs. on-premise/embedded): ~$720M-$4.8B by 2030\n   263→- Of those, perhaps 20-30% have active carbon offset commitments: ~$144M-$1.4B by 2030\n   264→\n   265→**Serviceable Obtainable Market (SOM)**: What Jagat Kalyan can realistically capture in the first 3-5 years.\n   266→- 1-3% of SAM in year 3: $1.4M-$43M annually\n   267→- This assumes establishing market presence, partnerships with 2-3 AI providers or large API consumers, and verified credit quality.\n   268→\n   269→**Revenue model**: Jagat Kalyan takes a percentage (5-15%) of the offset transaction as a platform fee, plus subscription fees for the attribution API.\n   270→\n   271→---\n   272→\n   273→## 5. Technical Architecture for Per-Inference Attribution\n   274→\n   275→### 5.1 API Middleware Approach (Primary Strategy)\n   276→\n   277→The most practical architecture wraps existing LLM API calls with a carbon estimation layer:\n   278→\n   279→```\n   280→Developer App\n   281→    |\n   282→    v\n   283→Jagat Kalyan SDK (Python/JS)\n   284→    |\n   285→    +---> Forward request to LLM Provider (OpenAI, Anthropic, etc.)\n   286→    +---> Capture: model name, input tokens, output tokens, timestamp\n   287→    +---> Lookup: model energy profile, provider region, grid carbon intensity\n   288→    +---> Calculate: Wh x PUE x gCO2/kWh = gCO2 per inference\n   289→    +---> Log: attribution record to Jagat Kalyan ledger\n   290→    +---> Optional: auto-purchase offset credit\n   291→    |\n   292→    v\n   293→Response returned to developer (with carbon metadata)\n   294→```\n   295→\n   296→**Advantages**: No provider cooperation needed. Works with any API-based model. Can launch immediately.\n   297→\n   298→**Disadvantages**: Estimation-based (not measured). Cannot know actual GPU type, batch size, or data center location for a specific query. Must use average assumptions.\n   299→\n   300→### 5.2 Provider-Side Integration (Partnership Strategy)\n   301→\n   302→If AI providers expose per-inference energy telemetry, attribution accuracy improves dramatically:\n   303→\n   304→```\n   305→LLM Provider (internal)\n   306→    |\n   307→    +---> GPU power meter (NVML / RAPL)\n   308→    +---> Actual compute time per request\n   309→    +---> Actual data center + grid region\n   310→    +---> Actual PUE for that facility\n   311→    |\n   312→    v\n   313→Provider API response headers:\n   314→    X-Energy-Wh: 0.38\n   315→    X-Carbon-gCO2: 0.15\n   316→    X-Data-Center: us-west-2\n   317→    X-Grid-Intensity: 245\n   318→```\n   319→\n   320→**Advantages**: Ground-truth accuracy. Provider-verified. Enables real differentiation.\n   321→\n   322→**Disadvantages**: Requires provider cooperation. No major provider currently offers this. Competitive sensitivity around efficiency data. 12-24 month partnership development cycle.\n   323→\n   324→**Feasibility note**: The GSF SCI for AI specification (ratified 2025) calls for provider-side disclosure of a \"provider score.\" This creates normative pressure for providers to expose this data. Google's carbon footprint dashboard already exports to BigQuery, suggesting openness to granular reporting.\n   325→\n   326→### 5.3 Client-Side Estimation (Fallback Strategy)\n   327→\n   328→For cases where neither middleware nor provider integration is available:\n   329→\n   330→1. **Token-counting approach**: Count input/output tokens, multiply by published energy-per-token estimates for the model family.\n   331→2. **Latency-based inference**: Use response latency as a proxy for compute time. Longer latency = more computation = more energy.\n   332→3. **Cost-based proxy**: API pricing correlates loosely with compute cost, which correlates with energy. $0.01 per 1K tokens implies a certain GPU-time allocation.\n   333→\n   334→**Accuracy**: +/-50-100%. Useful only as a rough order-of-magnitude estimate. Acceptable for consumer-facing \"awareness\" displays, not for carbon credit transactions.\n   335→\n   336→### 5.4 Accuracy vs. Precision Tradeoffs\n   337→\n   338→| Approach | Accuracy | Precision | Latency Impact | Provider Dependency |\n   339→|----------|----------|-----------|----------------|-------------------|\n   340→| Client-side estimation | +/-50-100% | Low | None | None |\n   341→| API middleware (static) | +/-40-60% | Medium | <5ms | None |\n   342→| API middleware (real-time grid) | +/-20-40% | Medium-High | <50ms | Grid API only |\n   343→| Provider-side telemetry | +/-5-10% | High | None (header) | Full |\n   344→\n   345→**Recommendation**: Start with API middleware using EcoLogits-calibrated estimates (Phase 1), layer in real-time grid data (Phase 2), pursue provider partnerships (Phase 3). This progression delivers value immediately while building toward high accuracy.\n   346→\n   347→---\n   348→\n   349→## 6. Feasibility Assessment\n   350→\n   351→### 6.1 Dimension Ratings\n   352→\n   353→| Dimension | Score (1-5) | Justification |\n   354→|-----------|-------------|---------------|\n   355→| **Data availability** | 3/5 | Energy benchmarks exist for major models. Grid carbon data is available via APIs. But per-inference ground truth from providers is unavailable. |\n   356→| **Technical complexity** | 4/5 | API wrapping is straightforward. EcoLogits proves the pattern. Real-time grid integration adds moderate complexity. The hard part is accuracy, not implementation. |\n   357→| **Market readiness** | 3/5 | Growing demand for carbon accountability. But buyer sophistication is low, and carbon credit quality concerns persist. AI companies are beginning to face pressure on energy transparency. |\n   358→| **Regulatory alignment** | 4/5 | ISO/IEC 21031 (SCI) provides a standard. EU AI Act includes sustainability reporting provisions. GSF SCI for AI creates sector-specific guidance. Regulatory tailwinds are strong. |\n   359→| **Partnership dependency** | 2/5 | MVP has zero partnership dependency (API middleware). But high-accuracy attribution requires provider cooperation, which is uncertain. No AI provider currently offers per-inference energy data via API. |\n   360→\n   361→**Overall feasibility score: 3.4/5 -- FEASIBLE WITH CAVEATS**\n   362→\n   363→The system is buildable and launchable with current technology and data. The primary risk is accuracy -- estimation-based attribution has inherent uncertainty that could undermine credibility if not communicated transparently. The primary dependency is on AI provider willingness to expose energy telemetry for Phase 3+.\n   364→\n   365→### 6.2 Key Assumptions\n   366→\n   367→1. **Energy benchmarks are roughly correct**: The published figures (0.24-4.05 Wh per query) are based on reasonable estimation methodologies, but none have been verified by providers.\n   368→2. **Grid carbon data remains accessible**: WattTime, ElectricityMaps, and similar APIs continue to operate and improve coverage.\n   369→3. **Voluntary carbon market grows**: If the VCM stalls or collapses due to integrity concerns, demand for AI-specific offsets would be limited.\n   370→4. **AI providers will eventually disclose**: Regulatory and market pressure will push toward per-inference energy transparency within 2-3 years.\n   371→5. **Offset demand correlates with awareness**: As developers see per-inference carbon costs, some percentage will pay for offsets.\n   372→\n   373→### 6.3 Key Risks\n   374→\n   375→| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n   376→|------|-----------|--------|------------|\n   377→| Estimation inaccuracy undermines credibility | Medium-High | High | Transparent uncertainty bounds; frame as \"estimated range\" not \"exact measurement\" |\n   378→| AI providers refuse to cooperate | Medium | Medium | Proceed with estimation-based approach; work with open-source/self-hosted models first |\n   379→| Voluntary carbon market contraction | Low-Medium | High | Diversify to compliance markets; focus on credit quality |\n   380→| Competitor launches first | Medium | Medium | First-mover advantage is less important than credit quality and developer experience |\n   381→| Regulatory changes invalidate methodology | Low | Medium | Align with ISO/IEC 21031 and GSF SCI for AI from the start |\n   382→| Greenwashing accusations | Medium | High | Conservative estimates, transparent methodology, third-party verification |\n   383→\n   384→### 6.4 What's Achievable by Phase\n   385→\n   386→**MVP (4 weeks)**:\n   387→- Python SDK wrapping OpenAI and Anthropic API calls.\n   388→- Static energy estimates per model (lookup table based on published benchmarks).\n   389→- Static carbon intensity per region (using provider's reported data center locations).\n   390→- Per-inference carbon estimate returned as metadata with each API response.\n   391→- Simple dashboard showing cumulative carbon footprint.\n   392→- Offset purchase integration with one credit provider (e.g., Patch, Cloverly).\n   393→- Accuracy: +/-50-60%.\n   394→\n   395→**v2 (6 months)**:\n   396→- EcoLogits integration or equivalent regression-based energy estimation.\n   397→- Real-time grid carbon intensity via WattTime or ElectricityMaps API.\n   398→- Support for 5+ LLM providers (OpenAI, Anthropic, Google, Mistral, Cohere).\n   399→- Time-of-day carbon intensity variation in estimates.\n   400→- SCI-aligned methodology documentation (ISO/IEC 21031 compliance).\n   401→- Developer API for programmatic access to carbon data.\n   402→- Carbon budget feature: set a per-project carbon limit.\n   403→- Accuracy: +/-20-40%.\n   404→\n   405→**v3 (12 months)**:\n   406→- Provider partnership with at least one AI company for actual telemetry.\n   407→- Self-hosted model support (CodeCarbon integration for local measurement).\n   408→- Carbon-aware routing: suggest the lowest-carbon model/region for a given task.\n   409→- Verified offset portfolio with multiple restoration project types.\n   410→- Enterprise reporting (Scope 2 AI emissions for sustainability reports).\n   411→- SCI for AI compliance certification.\n   412→- Accuracy: +/-10-20% (for partnered providers).\n   413→\n   414→**Full system (24 months)**:\n   415→- Scope 1/2/3 attribution including embodied hardware carbon.\n   416→- Hardware lifecycle data from GPU manufacturers (NVIDIA, AMD).\n   417→- Multi-provider carbon optimization engine.\n   418→- Real-time carbon-aware inference routing across providers.\n   419→- Blockchain or distributed ledger for attribution transparency.\n   420→- Integration with compliance carbon markets (EU ETS, Article 6.4).\n   421→- Accuracy: +/-5-10% (full telemetry partners).\n   422→\n   423→---\n   424→\n   425→## 7. Four-Phase Implementation Roadmap\n   426→\n   427→### Phase 1: MVP -- Static Estimation (Weeks 1-4)\n   428→\n   429→**Goal**: Ship a working per-inference carbon attribution SDK that developers can integrate in under 10 minutes.\n   430→\n   431→**Technical deliverables**:\n   432→- Python SDK with provider wrappers (OpenAI, Anthropic initially).\n   433→- Energy lookup table: model name -> estimated Wh per 1K input tokens, Wh per 1K output tokens.\n   434→- Static carbon intensity table: provider region -> gCO2/kWh (sourced from IEA Emissions Factors 2025).\n   435→- PUE table: provider -> average PUE (from public disclosures).\n   436→- Per-inference calculation: `gCO2 = (input_tokens * Wh_per_1K_input + output_tokens * Wh_per_1K_output) * PUE * gCO2_per_kWh / 1000`.\n   437→- Response wrapper that attaches `carbon_estimate_gCO2` to every API response.\n   438→- SQLite or Postgres logging of all attributions.\n   439→- Simple web dashboard (cumulative emissions, per-model breakdown, per-day trend).\n   440→- One-click offset purchase via Patch API or similar.\n   441→\n   442→**Data sources**:\n   443→- Epoch AI energy benchmarks.\n   444→- EcoLogits published model profiles.\n   445→- IEA Emissions Factors 2025.\n   446→- Google/AWS/Azure PUE disclosures.\n   447→\n   448→**Success criteria**:\n   449→- SDK works with OpenAI and Anthropic Python clients.\n   450→- <5ms additional latency per call.\n   451→- Carbon estimate within 2x of EcoLogits for same queries.\n   452→- 10+ beta users providing feedback.\n   453→\n   454→### Phase 2: Real-Time Grid Integration (Months 2-6)\n   455→\n   456→**Goal**: Replace static estimates with dynamic, time-aware carbon attribution.\n   457→\n   458→**Technical deliverables**:\n   459→- Integration with WattTime API (marginal emissions, 5-min granularity, US + EU coverage).\n   460→- Integration with ElectricityMaps API (200+ global zones, real-time + forecast).\n   461→- Provider region detection: map API response headers or endpoint URLs to approximate data center locations.\n   462→- Time-of-day adjustment: carbon intensity varies by hour; capture this in estimates.\n   463→- EcoLogits integration: use their regression models for energy estimation instead of static lookup tables.\n   464→- Expanded provider support: Google GenAI, Mistral, Cohere, Hugging Face Inference API.\n   465→- JavaScript/TypeScript SDK for Node.js developers.\n   466→- SCI methodology document: formal alignment with ISO/IEC 21031, published for review.\n   467→- API endpoint: `GET /v1/carbon?model=claude-3.5-sonnet&input_tokens=500&output_tokens=1000&timestamp=2026-03-11T14:00:00Z` returns estimated gCO2 with confidence interval.\n   468→\n   469→**Key integration**: EcoLogits' updated methodology (ML.ENERGY Leaderboard benchmarks) provides more accurate energy estimates than static tables. Their model profiles cover most major API-served models.\n   470→\n   471→**Success criteria**:\n   472→- Real-time grid data reduces estimation error by 30%+ vs. static averages.\n   473→- 100+ active SDK users.\n   474→- SCI methodology passes peer review by at least one sustainability domain expert.\n   475→\n   476→### Phase 3: Provider Partnerships (Months 6-18)\n   477→\n   478→**Goal**: Obtain actual per-inference energy data from at least one major AI provider.\n   479→\n   480→**Partnership targets** (in priority order):\n   481→1. **Google/DeepMind**: Most transparent on sustainability. Already exports carbon data to BigQuery. Best prospect for early partnership.\n   482→2. **Anthropic**: Mission-aligned (safety focus extends to externalities). No current energy disclosure, but philosophically receptive.\n   483→3. **Mistral**: European, subject to EU sustainability reporting requirements. Smaller company, potentially more agile.\n   484→4. **OpenAI/Microsoft**: Largest market share, but historically less transparent on operational metrics.\n   485→\n   486→**What we need from providers**:\n   487→- Per-request energy consumption (Wh), even if approximate.\n   488→- Data center region for the specific request.\n   489→- Hardware generation (e.g., H100 vs. A100) -- optional but valuable.\n   490→- Willingness to include energy metadata in API response headers.\n   491→\n   492→**What we offer providers**:\n   493→- Sustainability reporting compliance (SCI for AI, EU AI Act).\n   494→- Positive positioning as \"carbon-transparent\" providers.\n   495→- Access to offset marketplace (their customers can easily offset).\n   496→- Aggregate anonymized data on per-model carbon efficiency (competitive benchmarking).\n   497→\n   498→**Parallel track -- self-hosted models**:\n   499→- CodeCarbon integration for local GPU measurement.\n   500→- Support for Ollama, vLLM, TGI, and other local inference servers.\n   501→- Direct NVML/RAPL power measurement for ground-truth calibration.\n   502→\n   503→**Success criteria**:\n   504→- Signed partnership or MOU with at least one provider.\n   505→- Ground-truth validation: measured vs. estimated divergence < 20%.\n   506→- 500+ active SDK users.\n   507→- First enterprise customer generating SCI-compliant AI carbon reports.\n   508→\n   509→### Phase 4: Full Scope 1/2/3 + Hardware Lifecycle (Months 18-30)\n   510→\n   511→**Goal**: Complete lifecycle carbon attribution, including embodied emissions.\n   512→\n   513→**Technical deliverables**:\n   514→- Scope 3 embodied carbon model: amortize GPU manufacturing emissions over operational lifetime per inference.\n   515→- Hardware-specific profiles: NVIDIA H100 (~150-200 kgCO2 embodied), A100 (~100-150 kgCO2), TPUv5, AMD MI300X.\n   516→- Networking and storage carbon: include non-GPU infrastructure in attribution.\n   517→- Water usage attribution: AI inference consumes water for cooling; include water footprint (liters per inference).\n   518→- Carbon-aware routing engine: given a query, recommend the lowest-carbon model/provider/region/time combination.\n   519→- Compliance market integration: generate credits compatible with EU ETS or Article 6.4 registries.\n   520→- Audit trail: cryptographic verification of attribution chain from inference to offset retirement.\n   521→\n   522→**Data requirements**:\n   523→- GPU LCA data from NVIDIA/AMD (currently not publicly available at component level; may require direct partnership or use of academic LCA studies).\n   524→- AWS/Google/Azure hardware refresh cycle data (to calculate embodied carbon amortization).\n   525→- Water usage data per data center (Google publishes this; others are catching up).\n   526→\n   527→**Success criteria**:\n   528→- Full Scope 1/2/3 attribution for at least 2 providers.\n   529→- Third-party audit of methodology by accredited verifier.\n   530→- Integration with at least one compliance carbon market.\n   531→- 2,000+ active SDK users.\n   532→- $1M+ annual offset transactions flowing through the platform.\n   533→\n   534→---\n   535→\n   536→## 8. Competitive Landscape and Differentiation\n   537→\n   538→### 8.1 Existing Players\n   539→\n   540→| Company/Tool | What They Do | Gap vs. Jagat Kalyan |\n   541→|--------------|-------------|---------------------|\n   542→| EcoLogits | Per-inference estimation library | No offset marketplace; no real-time grid data; research tool, not platform |\n   543→| CodeCarbon | Local hardware measurement | Only works for self-hosted; no API inference support |\n   544→| Climatiq | Emission factor database API | Generic carbon factors; no AI-specific methodology |\n   545→| Patch / Cloverly | Carbon offset APIs | No AI-specific attribution; generic offset purchase |\n   546→| Cloud Carbon Footprint | Multi-cloud carbon reporting | Aggregate level; no per-inference granularity |\n   547→| Gravity Climate | AI emissions methodology | Early stage; methodology focus, not product |\n   548→\n   549→### 8.2 Jagat Kalyan's Differentiation\n   550→\n   551→1. **End-to-end**: Attribution + offset in one SDK call. No other tool connects measurement to action.\n   552→2. **Per-inference granularity**: The finest grain available. Cloud dashboards report monthly aggregates.\n   553→3. **Ecological restoration focus**: Offsets fund verified restoration projects, not generic carbon credits. Aligns with biodiversity co-benefits.\n   554→4. **Developer-first**: 10-minute integration. Drop-in wrapper for existing API calls.\n   555→5. **Standards-aligned**: ISO/IEC 21031 + GSF SCI for AI from day one.\n   556→\n   557→---\n   558→\n   559→## 9. Conclusion\n   560→\n   561→Per-inference carbon attribution is technically feasible today, commercially viable within 12 months, and strategically important as AI energy consumption scales from 15 TWh (2025) to 347 TWh (2030).\n   562→\n   563→The path is clear:\n   564→\n   565→1. **Now**: Ship a working SDK with estimation-based attribution. Accuracy is imperfect but sufficient to raise awareness and enable voluntary offsets.\n   566→2. **6 months**: Layer in real-time grid data and calibrated energy models. Accuracy improves to actionable levels.\n   567→3. **18 months**: Secure provider partnerships for actual telemetry. Attribution becomes verifiable.\n   568→4. **30 months**: Full lifecycle accounting with hardware embodied carbon. Platform becomes audit-grade.\n   569→\n   570→The market opportunity is real: AI inference will generate an estimated 6-121 MtCO2 annually by 2030, and the voluntary carbon market is growing to meet offset demand. Jagat Kalyan's per-inference attribution approach sits at the intersection of these two growth curves.\n   571→\n   572→The critical success factor is **credibility** -- transparent methodology, conservative estimates, uncertainty communication, and standards alignment. The worst outcome is being perceived as greenwashing. The best outcome is becoming the default carbon attribution layer for AI inference.\n   573→\n   574→---\n   575→\n   576→## References and Sources\n   577→\n   578→### Energy Consumption\n   579→- [How much energy does ChatGPT use? -- Epoch AI](https://epoch.ai/gradient-updates/how-much-energy-does-chatgpt-use)\n   580→- [AI Energy Use: The Hidden Cost of ChatGPT Queries -- IEEE Spectrum](https://spectrum.ieee.org/ai-energy-use)\n   581→- [What's the carbon footprint of using ChatGPT or Gemini? -- Hannah Ritchie](https://hannahritchie.substack.com/p/ai-footprint-august-2025)\n   582→- [How Hungry is AI? Benchmarking Energy, Water, and Carbon Footprint of LLM Inference -- arXiv](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.09598v1)\n   583→- [How Much Energy Does Anthropic's Claude AI Consume?](https://www.energycosts.co.uk/articles/anthropic-claude-ai-energy/)\n   584→- [Let's Analyze OpenAI's Claims About ChatGPT Energy Use -- Towards Data Science](https://towardsdatascience.com/lets-analyze-openais-claims-about-chatgpt-energy-use/)\n   585→\n   586→### Carbon Markets\n   587→- [Key trends in the 2026 voluntary carbon market -- Carbon Direct](https://www.carbon-direct.com/insights/key-trends-2026-voluntary-carbon-market)\n   588→- [Voluntary Carbon Market in 2026: Top Forecasts -- Carbon Credits](https://carboncredits.com/voluntary-carbon-market-in-2026-top-forecasts-and-what-they-mean-for-investors/)\n   589→- [A blueprint for scaling voluntary carbon markets -- McKinsey](https://www.mckinsey.com/capabilities/sustainability/our-insights/a-blueprint-for-scaling-voluntary-carbon-markets-to-meet-the-climate-challenge)\n   590→- [Voluntary Carbon Credit Market -- 50% CAGR for 2025-2030 -- Mordor Intelligence](https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/voluntary-carbon-credit-market---50-cagr-for-2025-2030-driven-by-expanding-corporate-net-zero-commitments-reports-mordor-intelligence-302595212.html)\n   591→\n   592→### AI Inference Market\n   593→- [AI Inference Market Size, Share & Growth, 2025 To 2030 -- MarketsandMarkets](https://www.marketsandmarkets.com/Market-Reports/ai-inference-market-189921964.html)\n   594→- [AI Inference Market Size And Trends -- Grand View Research](https://www.grandviewresearch.com/industry-analysis/artificial-intelligence-ai-inference-market-report)\n   595→\n   596→### Standards and Tools\n   597→- [Software Carbon Intensity (SCI) Specification -- Green Software Foundation](https://sci.greensoftware.foundation/)\n   598→- [ISO/IEC 21031:2024 -- Software Carbon Intensity](https://www.iso.org/standard/86612.html)\n   599→- [SCI for AI -- Green Software Foundation](https://sci-for-ai.greensoftware.foundation/)\n   600→- [New Standard Measures AI Carbon Footprint Across Lifecycle -- GSF](https://greensoftware.foundation/articles/sci-ai-specification-ratified-standard-for-measuring-ai-emissions-across-the/)\n   601→- [EcoLogits Documentation](https://ecologits.ai/latest/)\n   602→- [EcoLogits: Evaluating the Environmental Impacts of Generative AI -- JOSS](https://www.theoj.org/joss-papers/joss.07471/10.21105.joss.07471.pdf)\n   603→- [CodeCarbon](https://codecarbon.io/)\n   604→- [Ground-Truthing AI Energy Consumption: Validating CodeCarbon -- arXiv](https://arxiv.org/html/2509.22092v1)\n   605→\n   606→### Data Centers and Grid\n   607→- [Power usage effectiveness -- Google Data Centers](https://datacenters.google/efficiency/)\n   608→- [Carbon Dashboards in 2025: AWS vs Google vs Azure](https://medium.com/@robin_lemesle/carbon-dashboards-in-2025-aws-vs-google-vs-azure-a-reality-check-cd1c76412cfa)\n   609→- [Grid Carbon Intensity -- Green Agile](https://greenagile.org/metrics-and-impact/architecture-and-infrastructure/grid-carbon-intensity)\n   610→- [Lifecycle carbon intensity of electricity, 2025 -- Our World in Data](https://ourworldindata.org/grapher/carbon-intensity-electricity)\n   611→- [IEA Emissions Factors 2025](https://www.iea.org/data-and-statistics/data-product/emissions-factors-2025)\n   612→\n   613→### Scope 3 and Embodied Carbon\n   614→- [How AWS estimates embodied emissions of IT hardware](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/infrastructure-sustainability/how-aws-estimates-embodied-emissions-of-it-hardware-the-science-and-technology-behind-the-latest-customer-carbon-footprint-methodology/)\n   615→- [Demystifying data center Scope 3 carbon -- Schneider Electric](https://blog.se.com/datacenter/2023/07/11/demystifying-data-center-scope-3-carbon-with-our-findings/)\n   616→- [The carbon and water footprints of data centers -- ScienceDirect](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2666389925002788)\n   617→\n   618→### Architecture and Attribution\n   619→- [Federated carbon intelligence for sustainable AI -- Springer Nature](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1557/s43581-025-00146-1)\n   620→- [The Carbon-Aware Computing Ecosystem](https://medium.com/@davemasselink/the-carbon-aware-computing-ecosystem-progress-patterns-and-our-race-against-time-842a57cff529)\n   621→- [The carbon cost of an API call -- CIO](https://www.cio.com/article/4132293/the-carbon-cost-of-an-api-call.html)\n   622→- [Fair-CO2: Fair Attribution for Cloud Carbon Emissions -- ACM](https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/3695053.3731023)\n   623→"}]},"uuid":"5fff7ba8-71d4-4811-8b7e-7c3882cc98a0","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:20:26.751Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"dde6b1c7-5dbe-4635-a036-66549c7df0e0","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
