{"parentUuid":"03410f13-d53e-44cf-ac9e-b68c38ee9986","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"bash \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/hooks/run-with-flags-shell.sh\" \"post:observe\" \"skills/continuous-learning-v2/hooks/observe.sh\" \"standard,strict\""},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01KeBoEhwxZamgHykna1Da7G","toolUseID":"toolu_01KeBoEhwxZamgHykna1Da7G","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:20:41.538Z","uuid":"117e3f5d-17ee-4871-912c-9a82c632d097","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"117e3f5d-17ee-4871-912c-9a82c632d097","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01KeBoEhwxZamgHykna1Da7G","toolUseID":"toolu_01KeBoEhwxZamgHykna1Da7G","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:20:41.538Z","uuid":"d3999f22-94ef-4d53-a34b-9c3fce1e9f53","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"3ac660a1-f0cf-4af8-9793-97e5b1f2da5b","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"3cfdca64-d5a0-407a-b98d-81d58c820453","agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KeBoEhwxZamgHykna1Da7G","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Jagat Kalyan\n     2→\n     3→AI-coordinated ecological restoration matching platform. Connects AI companies' carbon budgets to community ecological restoration projects.\n     4→\n     5→*Parasparopagraho Jivanam* — Souls render service to one another.\n     6→\n     7→## Quick Start\n     8→\n     9→```bash\n    10→cd ~/jagat_kalyan\n    11→python3 -m venv .venv && source .venv/bin/activate\n    12→pip install -r requirements.txt\n    13→export ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...   # optional — falls back to heuristic matching\n    14→python app.py\n    15→```\n    16→\n    17→Open http://localhost:8000\n    18→\n    19→The database and seed data are created automatically on first startup.\n    20→\n    21→## What It Does\n    22→\n    23→- **Projects**: Register ecological restoration projects (mangrove, agroforestry, wetland, soil, ocean, etc.)\n    24→- **Funders**: Register AI companies with carbon footprints and offset budgets\n    25→- **Matching**: AI-powered multi-objective ranking (carbon x social x geographic x verification)\n    26→- **Outcomes**: Track carbon sequestered, jobs created, and welfare-tons\n    27→\n    28→## Matching Engine\n    29→\n    30→The matching endpoint sends funder profiles and project data to Claude, which ranks projects using a multiplicative welfare function:\n    31→\n    32→```\n    33→W = carbon_match * social_match * geographic_match * verification_match\n    34→```\n    35→\n    36→Zero in any dimension means zero welfare. A project must score well across ALL dimensions.\n    37→\n    38→If `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` is not set, falls back to heuristic scoring.\n    39→\n    40→## API Endpoints\n    41→\n    42→| Method | Path | Description |\n    43→|--------|------|-------------|\n    44→| GET | `/` | Dashboard |\n    45→| GET | `/projects` | Project listing + add form |\n    46→| POST | `/projects` | Create project (form) |\n    47→| GET | `/funders` | Funder listing + add form |\n    48→| POST | `/funders` | Create funder (form) |\n    49→| GET | `/matches` | Match viewer + generate form |\n    50→| POST | `/matches/generate` | Generate matches for a funder |\n    51→| GET | `/api/projects` | JSON: list projects |\n    52→| POST | `/api/projects` | JSON: create project |\n    53→| GET | `/api/funders` | JSON: list funders |\n    54→| POST | `/api/funders` | JSON: create funder |\n    55→| POST | `/api/matches/generate` | JSON: generate matches |\n    56→| GET | `/api/matches/{funder_id}` | JSON: get matches for funder |\n    57→| POST | `/api/outcomes` | JSON: record outcome |\n    58→| GET | `/api/dashboard` | JSON: summary stats |\n    59→\n    60→## Data Model\n    61→\n    62→Four tables: **Project**, **Funder**, **Match**, **Outcome**. SQLite database (`jagat_kalyan.db`), auto-created on first run. Auto-seeded with 5 restoration projects and 3 AI company funder profiles.\n    63→\n    64→## Seed Data\n    65→\n    66→5 real-ish restoration projects spanning mangrove (Bangladesh), soil (China), agroforestry (Niger), wetland (Brazil), and ocean (California). 3 AI company funders (Anthropic, OpenAI, DeepMind) with realistic carbon footprints and budgets.\n    67→\n    68→Re-seed manually: `python seed_data.py`\n    69→\n    70→## Stack\n    71→\n    72→- FastAPI + Jinja2 templates\n    73→- SQLAlchemy + SQLite\n    74→- Anthropic Python SDK (Claude API)\n    75→- No Docker, no complex deployment\n    76→"}]},"uuid":"546d181d-01e7-486d-bc79-53f8ca2d0094","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:20:41.538Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"3ac660a1-f0cf-4af8-9793-97e5b1f2da5b","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"546d181d-01e7-486d-bc79-53f8ca2d0094","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"bash \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/hooks/run-with-flags-shell.sh\" \"post:observe\" \"skills/continuous-learning-v2/hooks/observe.sh\" \"standard,strict\""},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_0191ThwynmkBFuRi3Fi1dM2B","toolUseID":"toolu_0191ThwynmkBFuRi3Fi1dM2B","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:20:41.820Z","uuid":"9d40f987-dd6a-4fee-87d7-1520d657c837","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"9d40f987-dd6a-4fee-87d7-1520d657c837","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_0191ThwynmkBFuRi3Fi1dM2B","toolUseID":"toolu_0191ThwynmkBFuRi3Fi1dM2B","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:20:41.820Z","uuid":"4e401d08-833e-411f-b2b0-f25ed0d48896","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"11eda081-3a03-47c0-b9da-065111f7ef14","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"3cfdca64-d5a0-407a-b98d-81d58c820453","agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0191ThwynmkBFuRi3Fi1dM2B","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Welfare-Tons: Mathematical Specification\n     2→\n     3→## The North Star Metric for Jagat Kalyan\n     4→\n     5→**Version**: 2.0\n     6→**Date**: 2026-03-11\n     7→**Author**: John \"Dhyana\" Shrader, with analytical support from Claude\n     8→**Status**: Draft specification -- ready for peer review and pilot calibration\n     9→**Revision note**: v2.0 restructures the formula to a flat 6-factor multiplicative architecture. v1.0 folded permanence into the carbon component and nested employment, agency, and other social indicators inside a composite $S$ multiplier. v2.0 promotes each dimension to a top-level factor: $W = C \\times E \\times A \\times B \\times V \\times P$. The motivation: zero in any dimension yields zero welfare-tons, with no possibility of hiding a deficit inside a composite.\n    10→\n    11→---\n    12→\n    13→## 0. Design Principles\n    14→\n    15→1. **Multiplicative, not additive.** Following the Jain principle *Parasparopagraho Jivanam* (souls render service to one another), welfare is indivisible. Zero in any dimension yields zero welfare-tons. You cannot trade ecological harm for social benefit. You cannot trade community displacement for carbon tonnage.\n    16→\n    17→2. **Zero kills the product.** If a project sequesters carbon but creates no jobs ($E = 0$), the welfare-tons are zero. If a project employs workers but the community never consented ($A = 0$), the welfare-tons are zero. This is the central enforcement mechanism against greenwashing: every dimension must be positive.\n    18→\n    19→3. **Conservative by default.** When data is missing or uncertain, sub-indicators default to their floor value. The metric rewards transparency and measurement, not optimistic self-reporting.\n    20→\n    21→4. **Compatible with existing standards.** The carbon component ($C$) follows Verra VCS and Gold Standard methodology in tCO2e. Employment metrics reference ILO Decent Work indicators. Biodiversity scoring references the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework. Verification architecture is compatible with ICVCM Core Carbon Principles.\n    22→\n    23→5. **Auditable and decomposable.** Every welfare-ton figure can be decomposed into its six factors ($C, E, A, B, V, P$), and every factor into its sub-indicators, with source data cited for each. The composite number is a summary; the components are the substance.\n    24→\n    25→6. **Normalized against a standard offset.** A conventional carbon credit with minimal employment, no community agency process, monoculture planting, satellite-only verification, and moderate permanence produces welfare-tons significantly below its raw tonnage. A community-led, biodiverse, well-verified, permanent restoration project produces welfare-tons 5-10x above the standard offset baseline, capturing value that carbon-only accounting ignores.\n    26→\n    27→---\n    28→\n    29→## 1. Master Formula\n    30→\n    31→$$W = C \\times E \\times A \\times B \\times V \\times P$$\n    32→\n    33→| Symbol | Name | Domain | Interpretation |\n    34→|--------|------|--------|----------------|\n    35→| $W$ | Welfare-tons | $[0, +\\infty)$ | Composite impact in welfare-ton-CO2e units |\n    36→| $C$ | Verified CO2 tons | $[0, +\\infty)$ | Net tCO2e sequestered or avoided per year |\n    37→| $E$ | Employment factor | $[0, E_{max}]$ | Job creation quality and density |\n    38→| $A$ | Community agency factor | $[0, 1]$ | Community consent, ownership, and self-determination |\n    39→| $B$ | Biodiversity co-benefit | $[0.8, 1.5]$ | Restoration type quality based on biodiversity indices |\n    40→| $V$ | Verification confidence | $[0, 1]$ | Trust in the underlying measurements |\n    41→| $P$ | Permanence factor | $[0, 1]$ | Risk-adjusted durability of sequestered carbon |\n    42→\n    43→**Units**: Welfare-tons are denominated in \"wt-CO2e\" to distinguish them from raw carbon tons. The unit is dimensionally equivalent to tCO2e but semantically distinct -- analogous to QALYs (quality-adjusted life years) in health economics, where the \"quality adjustment\" captures social, ecological, and verification dimensions that raw tonnage ignores.\n    44→\n    45→**Reporting rule**: All welfare-ton figures MUST be reported with the full six-factor decomposition alongside the composite number. A welfare-ton figure without its decomposition is incomplete and should not be cited in isolation.\n    46→\n    47→---\n    48→\n    49→## 2. Carbon Component ($C$)\n    50→\n    51→### 2.1 Definition\n    52→\n    53→$C$ is the net annual CO2-equivalent sequestration or avoidance attributable to the project, expressed in metric tons, after applying an additionality adjustment.\n    54→\n    55→$$C = C_{gross} \\times \\alpha_{add}$$\n    56→\n    57→| Symbol | Name | Domain | Definition |\n    58→|--------|------|--------|------------|\n    59→| $C_{gross}$ | Gross sequestration | $[0, +\\infty)$ tCO2e/yr | Total measured CO2e removed or avoided |\n    60→| $\\alpha_{add}$ | Additionality discount | $(0, 1]$ | Discount for counterfactual baseline |\n    61→\n    62→**Note on permanence**: In v1.0, permanence was folded into $C$ as $\\alpha_{perm}$. In v2.0, permanence is a top-level factor ($P$), applied multiplicatively at the same level as employment and biodiversity. This makes permanence risk visible and prevents it from being buried inside the carbon number.\n    63→\n    64→### 2.2 Gross Sequestration Measurement ($C_{gross}$)\n    65→\n    66→$C_{gross}$ is estimated using a three-layer measurement protocol:\n    67→\n    68→**Layer 1: Remote Sensing**\n    69→- Satellite multispectral imagery (Sentinel-2 at 10m, Planet Labs at 3m) for canopy cover, NDVI, and biomass estimation.\n    70→- LiDAR (where available) for above-ground biomass volumetric estimates.\n    71→- SAR for below-canopy biomass in dense forest and mangrove environments.\n    72→- Measurement frequency: Monthly composites, quarterly analysis.\n    73→- Uncertainty: Typically $\\pm$15-30% for above-ground biomass depending on ecosystem type (Chave et al. 2014).\n    74→\n    75→**Layer 2: Ground-Truth Calibration**\n    76→- Stratified random sampling: minimum 1 plot per 10 hectares (Pearson et al. 2007 VCS guidance).\n    77→- Each plot: DBH inventory, allometric biomass equations (species-specific where available).\n    78→- Soil organic carbon: Composite cores at 0-30cm and 30-100cm, laboratory dry combustion analysis.\n    79→- Community-based monitoring: Trained local workers collect plot data, cross-validated against expert surveys at 10% of plots.\n    80→\n    81→**Layer 3: Temporal Modeling**\n    82→- Bayesian hierarchical model incorporating remote sensing time series, ground-truth calibrations, and climate covariates.\n    83→- Reported value: Conservative estimate at the 80th percentile lower bound (80% probability that true sequestration exceeds the reported value), following the Verra VCS conservativeness principle.\n    84→\n    85→**Carbon Pool Coverage**:\n    86→\n    87→| Pool | Included | Method |\n    88→|------|----------|--------|\n    89→| Above-ground biomass | Yes | Remote sensing + plot inventory |\n    90→| Below-ground biomass | Yes | Root:shoot ratios |\n    91→| Soil organic carbon | Yes (ag/grassland/wetland) | Soil cores |\n    92→| Dead wood | Optional | Plot inventory if significant |\n    93→| Litter | Excluded | Minor pool, high measurement cost |\n    94→| Avoided emissions | Yes, if applicable | Baseline scenario modeling |\n    95→\n    96→### 2.3 Additionality Discount ($\\alpha_{add}$)\n    97→\n    98→Additionality tests whether sequestration would have occurred without the project. This is the most epistemically challenging component.\n    99→\n   100→$$\\alpha_{add} = 1 - P_{baseline}(\\text{sequestration occurs anyway})$$\n   101→\n   102→**Three-part test** (adapted from CDM and Gold Standard):\n   103→\n   104→**Test 1: Regulatory surplus.** Would the activity be required by law regardless of carbon finance? If yes: $\\alpha_{add} \\leq 0.3$.\n   105→\n   106→**Test 2: Financial additionality.** Is the project financially viable without carbon revenue? Compare project IRR with and without. If viable without carbon: $\\alpha_{add} = 0.5$.\n   107→\n   108→**Test 3: Barrier analysis.** Score three barriers:\n   109→\n   110→| Barrier | Weight | Score range |\n   111→|---------|--------|-------------|\n   112→| Financial (access to capital) | 0.40 | 0 (none) to 1 (severe) |\n   113→| Institutional (governance, permits) | 0.30 | 0 to 1 |\n   114→| Technical (knowledge, capacity) | 0.30 | 0 to 1 |\n   115→\n   116→$\\alpha_{add} = 0.5 + 0.5 \\times \\text{barrier\\_score}$, range $[0.5, 1.0]$.\n   117→\n   118→**Combined**: $\\alpha_{add} = \\max(\\text{Test1}, \\text{Test2}, \\text{Test3})$, using the strongest evidence of additionality.\n   119→\n   120→**Reference values**:\n   121→\n   122→| Scenario | $\\alpha_{add}$ |\n   123→|----------|-----------------|\n   124→| Degraded land, no alternative use | 0.95 |\n   125→| Former agricultural land in transition | 0.80 |\n   126→| Forest in region with active deforestation | 0.70 |\n   127→| Urban greening in mandated sustainability zone | 0.40 |\n   128→\n   129→---\n   130→\n   131→## 3. Employment Factor ($E$)\n   132→\n   133→### 3.1 Definition\n   134→\n   135→$E$ measures the density and quality of jobs created per unit of investment, normalized so that the target of 50+ jobs per $1M invested at 1.5x minimum wage receives an $E$ value in the range that drives the 5-10x amplification.\n   136→\n   137→$$E = E_{density} \\times E_{quality}$$\n   138→\n   139→### 3.2 Employment Density ($E_{density}$)\n   140→\n   141→$E_{density}$ measures jobs created per $1M invested, normalized against the target of 50 jobs/$1M.\n   142→\n   143→**Raw metric**: $j = \\text{FTE jobs created} / (\\text{total investment in \\$M})$\n   144→\n   145→**Continuous scoring**:\n   146→\n   147→$$E_{density} = \\frac{\\min(j, \\; j_{cap})}{j_{ref}}$$\n   148→\n   149→where:\n   150→- $j_{ref} = 25$ (the reference point: a standard carbon offset with minimal employment generates roughly 25 jobs per $1M, based on ILO forestry employment data)\n   151→- $j_{cap} = 100$ (cap to prevent extreme values from projects with very low capital intensity)\n   152→\n   153→This yields:\n   154→\n   155→| Jobs per $1M | $E_{density}$ | Interpretation |\n   156→|---------------|----------------|----------------|\n   157→| 0 | 0 | No employment -- **kills the product** |\n   158→| 10 | 0.40 | Low density (large-scale mechanized) |\n   159→| 25 | 1.00 | Reference (standard offset baseline) |\n   160→| 50 | 2.00 | Target (labor-intensive restoration) |\n   161→| 75 | 3.00 | High density (community cooperative) |\n   162→| 100+ | 4.00 | Maximum (capped) |\n   163→\n   164→**Why the cap matters**: Without it, a project could inflate $E_{density}$ by hiring 500 people for trivial tasks. The cap at 100 jobs/$1M, combined with the wage quality floor (below), prevents this. At $1M investment, 100 jobs at 1.5x minimum wage in a developing economy consumes essentially the entire budget in payroll -- any higher and the numbers are implausible or the wages are poverty-level.\n   165→\n   166→### 3.3 Employment Quality ($E_{quality}$)\n   167→\n   168→$E_{quality}$ captures whether the jobs are decent work, not just headcount. It integrates three sub-dimensions:\n   169→\n   170→$$E_{quality} = q_{wage} \\times q_{local} \\times q_{duration}$$\n   171→\n   172→#### 3.3.1 Wage Quality ($q_{wage}$)\n   173→\n   174→The wage floor is a hard constraint: projects paying below 1.5x local minimum wage receive a steep penalty.\n   175→\n   176→$$q_{wage} = \\begin{cases} 0.3 & \\text{if } w < 1.0 \\times MW \\\\[6pt] 0.3 + 0.7 \\times \\dfrac{w/MW - 1.0}{0.5} & \\text{if } 1.0 \\leq w/MW < 1.5 \\\\[6pt] 1.0 + 0.25 \\times \\min\\left(\\dfrac{w/MW - 1.5}{1.0}, \\; 1.0\\right) & \\text{if } w/MW \\geq 1.5 \\end{cases}$$\n   177→\n   178→where $w$ is the average worker wage and $MW$ is the local minimum wage (PPP-adjusted for cross-country comparisons).\n   179→\n   180→| Wage / Minimum Wage | $q_{wage}$ | Note |\n   181→|----------------------|------------|------|\n   182→| < 1.0x | 0.30 | Severe penalty; likely disqualifying |\n   183→| 1.0x | 0.30 | At minimum wage -- still penalized |\n   184→| 1.25x | 0.65 | Below target floor |\n   185→| 1.5x (target floor) | 1.00 | Meets Jagat Kalyan standard |\n   186→| 2.0x | 1.125 | Good wages |\n   187→| 2.5x+ | 1.25 | Excellent wages (capped) |\n   188→\n   189→**Anti-gaming mechanism**: The wage floor is non-negotiable. A project cannot hire 200 workers at $0.50/day to inflate $E_{density}$ because $q_{wage} = 0.30$ would crush the product. The interaction $E_{density} \\times q_{wage}$ means you need BOTH quantity AND quality. Specifically: 100 workers at below-minimum wage yields $E = 4.0 \\times 0.30 \\times q_{local} \\times q_{duration} \\approx 1.2$ at best, which is worse than 50 workers at 1.5x minimum ($E = 2.0 \\times 1.0 \\times q_{local} \\times q_{duration} \\approx 2.0$). The math rewards quality over raw headcount.\n   190→\n   191→#### 3.3.2 Local Labor ($q_{local}$)\n   192→\n   193→$$q_{local} = 0.5 + 0.5 \\times f_{local}$$\n   194→\n   195→where $f_{local}$ is the fraction of workers who are local residents (defined as residing within 50 km of the project site for at least 12 months prior to employment).\n   196→\n   197→| Fraction local | $q_{local}$ |\n   198→|----------------|-------------|\n   199→| 0% | 0.50 |\n   200→| 50% | 0.75 |\n   201→| 90% | 0.95 |\n   202→| 100% | 1.00 |\n   203→\n   204→#### 3.3.3 Employment Duration ($q_{duration}$)\n   205→\n   206→$$q_{duration} = 0.5 + 0.5 \\times \\min\\left(\\frac{d}{12}, \\; 1.0\\right)$$\n   207→\n   208→where $d$ is the average contract duration in months.\n   209→\n   210→| Duration | $q_{duration}$ |\n   211→|----------|----------------|\n   212→| Seasonal, 3 months | 0.625 |\n   213→| 6 months | 0.75 |\n   214→| 12+ months | 1.00 |\n   215→\n   216→### 3.4 Composite $E$ Calculation\n   217→\n   218→$$E = E_{density} \\times E_{quality} = \\frac{\\min(j, \\; 100)}{25} \\times q_{wage} \\times q_{local} \\times q_{duration}$$\n   219→\n   220→**Theoretical bounds**:\n   221→- Minimum: $E = 0$ (no jobs created)\n   222→- Baseline (standard offset): $E \\approx 1.0$ (25 jobs/$1M at reference wages)\n   223→- Target: $E \\approx 2.0$ (50 jobs/$1M at 1.5x MW, local, year-round)\n   224→- Maximum: $E = 4.0 \\times 1.25 \\times 1.0 \\times 1.0 = 5.0$\n   225→\n   226→### 3.5 Data Collection Requirements\n   227→\n   228→| Data point | Source | Frequency | Verification |\n   229→|------------|--------|-----------|--------------|\n   230→| FTE job count | Payroll records | Monthly | Cross-check with tax filings and site visits |\n   231→| Total investment | Financial statements | Annual | Third-party audit |\n   232→| Average wage | Payroll records (disaggregated) | Monthly | Comparison to national MW database |\n   233→| Worker residence | Employment contracts + ID verification | At hire | Random spot-check by assessor |\n   234→| Contract duration | Employment contracts | At hire + renewal | HR records audit |\n   235→\n   236→---\n   237→\n   238→## 4. Community Agency Factor ($A$)\n   239→\n   240→### 4.1 Definition\n   241→\n   242→$A$ measures whether the community chose the project. It is a consent protocol score on $[0, 1]$ with a clear interpretation: $A = 0$ means the community was not consulted, and the project earns zero welfare-tons. $A = 1$ means the community initiated and governs the project.\n   243→\n   244→This factor operationalizes Free, Prior, and Informed Consent (FPIC) as articulated by the UN Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples and the IFC Performance Standards.\n   245→\n   246→### 4.2 Scoring Rubric\n   247→\n   248→$A$ is the weighted sum of four dimensions, each scored on $[0, 1]$:\n   249→\n   250→$$A = 0.30 \\times A_{init} + 0.25 \\times A_{gov} + 0.25 \\times A_{own} + 0.20 \\times A_{veto}$$\n   251→\n   252→#### 4.2.1 Project Initiation ($A_{init}$)\n   253→\n   254→| Score | Description |\n   255→|-------|-------------|\n   256→| 0.0 | Imposed with no community knowledge or input |\n   257→| 0.2 | Community informed after project designed |\n   258→| 0.4 | Community consulted during design, input not binding |\n   259→| 0.6 | Community co-designed the project with external partner |\n   260→| 0.8 | Community initiated with external technical support |\n   261→| 1.0 | Community conceived, designed, and sought external support |\n   262→\n   263→#### 4.2.2 Governance Structure ($A_{gov}$)\n   264→\n   265→| Score | Description |\n   266→|-------|-------------|\n   267→| 0.0 | No community representation in governance |\n   268→| 0.3 | Advisory role, no decision power |\n   269→| 0.5 | Shared governance (50/50 community/external) |\n   270→| 0.7 | Community majority governance |\n   271→| 1.0 | Community-governed with external advisory only |\n   272→\n   273→#### 4.2.3 Ownership of Assets and Credits ($A_{own}$)\n   274→\n   275→| Score | Description |\n   276→|-------|-------------|\n   277→| 0.0 | 100% external ownership of credits and assets |\n   278→| 0.3 | Revenue sharing (<30% to community) |\n   279→| 0.5 | Significant co-ownership (30-50% community) |\n   280→| 0.7 | Majority community ownership (50-70%) |\n   281→| 1.0 | Community owns >70% of credits and retains all land rights |\n   282→\n   283→#### 4.2.4 Veto Power ($A_{veto}$)\n   284→\n   285→| Score | Description |\n   286→|-------|-------------|\n   287→| 0.0 | No mechanism to halt or modify project |\n   288→| 0.3 | Grievance mechanism exists but non-binding |\n   289→| 0.5 | Can block specific activities with documented cause |\n   290→| 0.7 | Can halt project with cause, binding arbitration |\n   291→| 1.0 | Unconditional veto right, exercisable at any time |\n   292→\n   293→### 4.3 Interpretation\n   294→\n   295→| $A$ range | Label | Welfare-ton impact |\n   296→|-----------|-------|--------------------|\n   297→| 0.0 | No consent | $W = 0$ (product killed) |\n   298→| 0.01 - 0.29 | Imposed | Severe discount; automatically flagged |\n   299→| 0.30 | Top-down threshold | Minimum for standard offsets with consultation |\n   300→| 0.50 | Co-designed | Meaningful community participation |\n   301→| 0.70 | Community-majority | Strong community ownership |\n   302→| 0.90 - 1.00 | Community-led | Full agency; maximum credit |\n   303→\n   304→**The design intent**: Projects imposed top-down get $A \\approx 0.3$, which discounts welfare-tons by 70%. Community-led projects get $A \\approx 0.9 - 1.0$, preserving nearly all value. This creates a powerful economic incentive for genuine community partnership.\n   305→\n   306→**Anti-gaming mechanism**: $A$ cannot be inflated by performative consultation. The scoring rubric requires verifiable structural features (governance seats, ownership percentages, legal veto rights) rather than self-reported \"satisfaction.\" Specifically:\n   307→- $A_{gov}$ requires documented governance structure with named community representatives.\n   308→- $A_{own}$ requires auditable ownership records for carbon credits and land tenure.\n   309→- $A_{veto}$ requires a legal instrument granting veto power, not merely a stated policy.\n   310→\n   311→### 4.4 Data Collection Requirements\n   312→\n   313→| Data point | Source | Frequency | Verification |\n   314→|------------|--------|-----------|--------------|\n   315→| Project initiation history | Documented timeline with dated correspondence | At inception | Third-party review of project genesis |\n   316→| Governance composition | Board minutes, membership records | Annual | Independent governance audit |\n   317→| Ownership structure | Legal documents, credit registry records | Annual | Legal audit + credit registry verification |\n   318→| Veto mechanism | Legal instrument (MOU, charter, contract) | At inception + annual review | Legal review |\n   319→| Community perception | Structured interviews, $n \\geq 30$ or 10% of affected population | Annual | Dual-rater coding, $\\kappa > 0.7$ |\n   320→\n   321→---\n   322→\n   323→## 5. Biodiversity Co-Benefit ($B$)\n   324→\n   325→### 5.1 Definition\n   326→\n   327→$B$ is a restoration type hierarchy based on peer-reviewed biodiversity indices. Unlike $E$ and $A$, which range from 0 upward, $B$ can fall below 1.0 for ecologically harmful project types. This means monoculture plantations are actively penalized, not merely unrewarded.\n   328→\n   329→### 5.2 Restoration Type Hierarchy\n   330→\n   331→The base $B$ values are derived from systematic reviews of biodiversity outcomes by restoration type (Crouzeilles et al. 2016, Gann et al. 2019, Lewis et al. 2019):\n   332→\n   333→| Restoration Type | $B_{base}$ | Evidence Basis |\n   334→|------------------|------------|----------------|\n   335→| Mangrove restoration | 1.50 | Highest combined biodiversity + carbon density. Supports 3-5x more fish species than degraded coastline (Nagelkerken et al. 2008). Nursery habitat for 75% of commercial fish species in tropical regions. |\n   336→| Native multi-species agroforestry | 1.30 | 50-80% of native forest bird species richness (Bhagwat et al. 2008). Supports pollinators, soil biota, and structural complexity. |\n   337→| Wetland/peatland restoration | 1.30 | Disproportionate biodiversity value per hectare. Critical habitat for amphibians, waterfowl, and invertebrates. High carbon density in peat. |\n   338→| Native grassland restoration | 1.10 | Important for grassland specialist species (declining globally). Lower absolute biodiversity than forest but high conservation value for endemic species. |\n   339→| Seagrass/kelp restoration | 1.20 | High fish nursery value and coastal ecosystem support. Growing evidence base (Unsworth et al. 2019). |\n   340→| Reforestation (mixed native) | 1.20 | Biodiversity recovery depends strongly on species mix and site history. |\n   341→| Urban green infrastructure | 1.00 | Modest biodiversity gains; primary value is social/microclimate. |\n   342→| Monoculture plantation | 0.80 | Penalty. Monoculture eucalyptus or pine supports <20% of native forest species richness (Brockerhoff et al. 2008). Often displaces native grassland or scrub with higher conservation value. |\n   343→\n   344→### 5.3 Biodiversity Adjustment ($B_{adj}$)\n   345→\n   346→The base value $B_{base}$ may be adjusted by $\\pm 0.2$ based on project-specific biodiversity evidence:\n   347→\n   348→$$B = B_{base} + B_{adj}$$\n   349→\n   350→where $B_{adj} \\in [-0.2, +0.2]$ based on:\n   351→\n   352→| Adjustment | $B_{adj}$ | Criterion |\n   353→|------------|-----------|-----------|\n   354→| IUCN Red List species present | +0.10 to +0.20 | Documented EN or CR species in project area |\n   355→| Habitat connectivity contribution | +0.05 to +0.10 | Project connects fragmented habitat patches |\n   356→| Measured Shannon-Wiener improvement >50% | +0.10 | $H'_{current} / H'_{baseline} > 1.5$ after $\\geq$ 2 survey cycles |\n   357→| Invasive species introduction risk | -0.10 to -0.20 | Non-native species comprise >20% of planted material |\n   358→| Low species diversity in planted material | -0.05 to -0.10 | Fewer than 5 native species planted |\n   359→\n   360→**Bounds**: $B \\in [0.6, 1.7]$ after adjustment, hard-capped.\n   361→\n   362→### 5.4 Data Collection Requirements\n   363→\n   364→| Data point | Source | Frequency | Verification |\n   365→|------------|--------|-----------|--------------|\n   366→| Restoration type classification | Project design documents | At inception | Site visit confirmation |\n   367→| Species planted / managed | Planting records, nursery inventory | Annual | Spot-check by ecologist |\n   368→| Shannon-Wiener diversity index | Species abundance surveys (plants: 1ha plots; birds: point counts; invertebrates: pitfall traps) | Annual (min 2 cycles before adjustment) | Expert validation at 10% of sites |\n   369→| IUCN species presence | Camera traps, expert surveys | Annual | Cross-reference IUCN database |\n   370→| Invasive species monitoring | Plot surveys | Semi-annual | Expert review |\n   371→\n   372→---\n   373→\n   374→## 6. Verification Confidence ($V$)\n   375→\n   376→### 6.1 Definition\n   377→\n   378→$V$ measures how much we can trust the data underlying all other factors. It is NOT a measure of project quality -- it is a measure of measurement quality. An excellent project with poor verification scores low $V$, and this is correct: we cannot credit what we cannot verify.\n   379→\n   380→### 6.2 Three-Tier Additive Structure\n   381→\n   382→$V$ is constructed additively from three verification tiers, each contributing a fixed increment:\n   383→\n   384→$$V = V_{sat} + V_{ground} + V_{ledger}$$\n   385→\n   386→| Tier | Component | Value | Criterion |\n   387→|------|-----------|-------|-----------|\n   388→| Tier 1 | Satellite monitoring ($V_{sat}$) | 0.50 | Systematic remote sensing analysis covering the project area |\n   389→| Tier 2 | Community ground-truth ($V_{ground}$) | +0.30 | Community monitors collecting field data using standardized protocols, cross-validated by expert ecologists |\n   390→| Tier 3 | Transparent ledger ($V_{ledger}$) | +0.20 | All measurement data, financial records, and governance documents published on a transparent, tamper-evident ledger (blockchain, public registry, or equivalent) |\n   391→\n   392→**Maximum**: $V = 0.50 + 0.30 + 0.20 = 1.0$\n   393→\n   394→**Interpretation**:\n   395→\n   396→| $V$ | Verification level | What it means |\n   397→|-----|-------------------|---------------|\n   398→| 0.0 | None | No verification of any kind -- $W = 0$ |\n   399→| 0.50 | Satellite only | Remote sensing confirms project exists and has carbon stock; no ground calibration, no public data |\n   400→| 0.80 | Satellite + ground-truth | Remote sensing calibrated by field measurements; data not publicly accessible |\n   401→| 1.00 | Full transparency | All three tiers active; data is publicly auditable |\n   402→\n   403→### 6.3 Tier Specifications\n   404→\n   405→#### 6.3.1 Satellite Monitoring ($V_{sat}$)\n   406→\n   407→To qualify for $V_{sat} = 0.50$, the project must demonstrate:\n   408→\n   409→- Systematic analysis of satellite imagery (Sentinel-2, Planet, or equivalent) covering the entire project boundary.\n   410→- Analysis frequency: minimum quarterly.\n   411→- Change detection: Documented methodology for detecting deforestation, degradation, fire, or land-use change within the project boundary.\n   412→- Imagery archive: All source imagery and analysis products retained for the project duration.\n   413→\n   414→$V_{sat}$ is binary: 0 or 0.50. There is no partial credit for \"some\" satellite analysis. Either a systematic remote sensing pipeline exists, or it does not.\n   415→\n   416→#### 6.3.2 Community Ground-Truth ($V_{ground}$)\n   417→\n   418→To qualify for $V_{ground} = 0.30$, the project must demonstrate:\n   419→\n   420→- Community monitors (trained local workers) collecting field data on a standardized schedule (minimum biannual).\n   421→- Standardized protocols for biomass plots, soil sampling, species surveys, or other relevant measurements.\n   422→- Expert validation: Independent ecologist or forester cross-validates community data at $\\geq$ 10% of measurement plots annually.\n   423→- Data chain: Ground-truth data linked to specific satellite analysis products for calibration.\n   424→\n   425→$V_{ground}$ has two levels:\n   426→\n   427→| Level | Value | Criterion |\n   428→|-------|-------|-----------|\n   429→| None | 0.00 | No ground-truth data collection |\n   430→| Partial (self-reported, no expert validation) | 0.15 | Ground data exists but unvalidated |\n   431→| Full (community monitoring + expert validation) | 0.30 | Complete ground-truth pipeline |\n   432→\n   433→#### 6.3.3 Transparent Ledger ($V_{ledger}$)\n   434→\n   435→To qualify for $V_{ledger} = 0.20$, the project must demonstrate:\n   436→\n   437→- All measurement data (satellite products, ground-truth records, carbon calculations) published to a publicly accessible registry.\n   438→- Financial records (investment amounts, payroll, procurement) available for third-party audit.\n   439→- Governance documents (board minutes, community consultation records, veto mechanism documentation) publicly accessible.\n   440→- Tamper evidence: Data published to a system where retroactive modification is detectable (blockchain, git-based registry with signed commits, or audited database with immutable append-only log).\n   441→\n   442→$V_{ledger}$ has two levels:\n   443→\n   444→| Level | Value | Criterion |\n   445→|-------|-------|-----------|\n   446→| None | 0.00 | Data is private |\n   447→| Partial (some data public, no tamper evidence) | 0.10 | Published reports without systematic transparency |\n   448→| Full (all data public + tamper-evident) | 0.20 | Complete transparency pipeline |\n   449→\n   450→### 6.4 Recency Modifier\n   451→\n   452→Verification confidence degrades over time. If the most recent verification event (satellite analysis, ground-truth collection, or ledger update) is more than 12 months old, $V$ is discounted:\n   453→\n   454→$$V_{effective} = V \\times \\delta_{recency}$$\n   455→\n   456→| Time since last verification | $\\delta_{recency}$ |\n   457→|------------------------------|---------------------|\n   458→| $\\leq$ 6 months | 1.00 |\n   459→| 6-12 months | 0.95 |\n   460→| 1-2 years | 0.85 |\n   461→| 2-3 years | 0.70 |\n   462→| > 3 years | 0.50 |\n   463→\n   464→### 6.5 Data Collection Requirements\n   465→\n   466→| Data point | Source | Frequency | Verification |\n   467→|------------|--------|-----------|--------------|\n   468→| Satellite analysis products | Remote sensing pipeline | Quarterly minimum | Retained imagery archive |\n   469→| Ground-truth measurement records | Community monitors | Biannual minimum | Expert cross-validation at 10% of plots |\n   470→| Expert validation reports | Independent ecologist/forester | Annual | Assessor credentials verified |\n   471→| Ledger publication status | Public registry / blockchain | Continuous | Third-party registry audit |\n   472→| Last verification date | All sources | Tracked per-event | Timestamped records |\n   473→\n   474→---\n   475→\n   476→## 7. Permanence Factor ($P$)\n   477→\n   478→### 7.1 Definition\n   479→\n   480→$P$ captures the risk that sequestered carbon is re-released within the commitment period. A project with high permanence ($P = 0.9$) retains 90% of its value; a project with high reversal risk ($P = 0.5$) retains only 50%.\n   481→\n   482→$$P = 1 - P_{reversal}(T)$$\n   483→\n   484→where $P_{reversal}(T)$ is the estimated probability of significant ($>$25%) carbon stock reversal over the commitment horizon $T$.\n   485→\n   486→### 7.2 Default Values by Ecosystem Type\n   487→\n   488→Default values are derived from IPCC AR6 Working Group III (Chapter 7), Seddon et al. (2020), and Verra buffer pool methodology:\n   489→\n   490→| Ecosystem Type | $P$ (T=25yr) | $P$ (T=50yr) | $P$ (T=100yr) | Rationale |\n   491→|----------------|--------------|--------------|----------------|-----------|\n   492→| Mangrove restoration | 0.90 | 0.85 | 0.75 | High carbon density (1,000 tC/ha). Strong root systems anchor sediment. Vulnerable to sea-level rise but resilient to storms if intact. Community stewardship strongly reduces reversal risk. |\n   493→| Native reforestation (multi-species) | 0.85 | 0.80 | 0.70 | Diverse species confer resilience. Fire, drought, disease risks moderated by diversity. Land tenure uncertainty in tropics. |\n   494→| Wetland/peatland restoration | 0.90 | 0.85 | 0.80 | Very high carbon density. Stable if hydrology maintained. Risk from drainage and fire in dry conditions. |\n   495→| Agroforestry | 0.80 | 0.70 | 0.60 | Diverse systems but dependent on farmer participation. Economic incentives may shift over decades. |\n   496→| Grassland restoration | 0.70 | 0.60 | 0.50 | Soil carbon is primary pool. Requires ongoing management. Vulnerable to land-use change and overgrazing. |\n   497→| Regenerative agriculture (SOC) | 0.70 | 0.60 | 0.50 | Reversible if practices abandoned. Soil saturation limits. Requires ongoing management incentives. |\n   498→| Soil carbon (general) | 0.50 | 0.40 | 0.30 | Lowest permanence. Highly sensitive to management changes. Limited depth. |\n   499→| Monoculture plantation | 0.65 | 0.50 | 0.35 | High disease/pest vulnerability, economic pressure for harvesting, low ecological resilience. |\n   500→| Seagrass/kelp | 0.75 | 0.65 | 0.50 | Vulnerable to water quality, temperature, storm damage. Shorter-lived carbon pool. |"}]},"uuid":"9d355910-7345-4ba0-ac2b-834c609e079a","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:20:41.820Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"11eda081-3a03-47c0-b9da-065111f7ef14","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
