{"parentUuid":"8b4aa7f4-f540-4181-81c3-ecf1a91c1b32","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"bash \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/hooks/run-with-flags-shell.sh\" \"post:observe\" \"skills/continuous-learning-v2/hooks/observe.sh\" \"standard,strict\""},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01GCcSqdvoGyQj2poGe2mH75","toolUseID":"toolu_01GCcSqdvoGyQj2poGe2mH75","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:20:51.055Z","uuid":"970078e5-5224-48f4-aa49-b129a31f77e5","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"970078e5-5224-48f4-aa49-b129a31f77e5","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01GCcSqdvoGyQj2poGe2mH75","toolUseID":"toolu_01GCcSqdvoGyQj2poGe2mH75","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:20:51.055Z","uuid":"507759b1-b2e0-43db-bacb-37e39c904a1c","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"4896c88e-314c-4bdb-b129-f480f9bdaf88","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"3cfdca64-d5a0-407a-b98d-81d58c820453","agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GCcSqdvoGyQj2poGe2mH75","type":"tool_result","content":"   500→| Seagrass/kelp | 0.75 | 0.65 | 0.50 | Vulnerable to water quality, temperature, storm damage. Shorter-lived carbon pool. |\n   501→\n   502→**Default commitment horizon**: $T = 25$ years, consistent with Gold Standard and Verra VCS minimum crediting periods.\n   503→\n   504→### 7.3 Project-Specific Adjustments\n   505→\n   506→The default $P$ may be adjusted by $\\pm 0.10$ based on project-specific risk assessment:\n   507→\n   508→| Adjustment | Effect on $P$ | Criterion |\n   509→|------------|---------------|-----------|\n   510→| Secure land tenure (>50 yr legal protection) | +0.05 | Documented legal tenure or conservation easement |\n   511→| Community stewardship commitment | +0.05 | Governance structure with documented long-term maintenance plan |\n   512→| Fire risk in fire-prone region | -0.05 to -0.10 | Project in region with >10% annual burn probability |\n   513→| Political instability | -0.05 to -0.10 | Country risk index in bottom quartile (World Bank Governance Indicators) |\n   514→| Insurance/buffer pool | +0.05 | Project contributes to pooled buffer account covering 10-20% of credits |\n   515→\n   516→**Bounds**: $P$ cannot exceed 0.95 (acknowledging irreducible uncertainty) or fall below 0.20 (at which point the project is flagged as non-viable for welfare-ton crediting).\n   517→\n   518→### 7.4 Data Collection Requirements\n   519→\n   520→| Data point | Source | Frequency | Verification |\n   521→|------------|--------|-----------|--------------|\n   522→| Ecosystem type classification | Project design documents + site assessment | At inception | Site visit confirmation |\n   523→| Land tenure documentation | Legal records | At inception + annual review | Legal audit |\n   524→| Fire risk assessment | Remote sensing fire history + regional climate data | Annual | Independent risk assessor |\n   525→| Political stability indicators | World Bank Governance Indicators | Annual | Public data |\n   526→| Buffer pool contribution | Financial records | Annual | Portfolio-level audit |\n   527→\n   528→---\n   529→\n   530→## 8. Example Calculations\n   531→\n   532→### 8.1 Scenario A: Standard Carbon Offset (Monoculture Tree Plantation, Uruguay)\n   533→\n   534→**Project**: 500-hectare monoculture eucalyptus plantation. No community employment component. Standard Verra VCS verification. Externally owned and managed.\n   535→\n   536→**Carbon ($C$)**:\n   537→- $C_{gross} = 3{,}500$ tCO2e/yr (eucalyptus: ~7 tCO2e/ha/yr)\n   538→- $\\alpha_{add} = 0.80$ (degraded pasture, would not have been planted without carbon finance)\n   539→- $C = 3{,}500 \\times 0.80 = 2{,}800$ tCO2e/yr\n   540→\n   541→**Employment ($E$)**:\n   542→- Total investment: ~$175K/yr. 5 FTE workers.\n   543→- $j = 5 / 0.175 = 28.6$ jobs per $1M\n   544→- $E_{density} = 28.6 / 25 = 1.14$\n   545→- Workers at minimum wage: $q_{wage} = 0.30$\n   546→- 80% local: $q_{local} = 0.90$\n   547→- Seasonal 6-month contracts: $q_{duration} = 0.75$\n   548→- $E_{quality} = 0.30 \\times 0.90 \\times 0.75 = 0.203$\n   549→- **$E = 1.14 \\times 0.203 = 0.231$**\n   550→\n   551→**Community Agency ($A$)**:\n   552→- Externally conceived ($A_{init} = 0.2$), external management ($A_{gov} = 0.0$), external ownership ($A_{own} = 0.0$), no veto ($A_{veto} = 0.0$)\n   553→- $A = 0.30 \\times 0.2 + 0.25 \\times 0.0 + 0.25 \\times 0.0 + 0.20 \\times 0.0 = 0.06$\n   554→\n   555→**Biodiversity ($B$)**:\n   556→- Monoculture plantation: $B_{base} = 0.80$\n   557→- No biodiversity adjustment data: $B_{adj} = 0$\n   558→- **$B = 0.80$**\n   559→\n   560→**Verification ($V$)**:\n   561→- Satellite: Annual Verra VCS satellite review. $V_{sat} = 0.50$\n   562→- Ground-truth: Annual self-reported data, no expert validation. $V_{ground} = 0.15$\n   563→- Ledger: Data submitted to Verra but not fully transparent. $V_{ledger} = 0.10$\n   564→- $V = 0.50 + 0.15 + 0.10 = 0.75$\n   565→- Last verification 8 months ago: $\\delta_{recency} = 0.95$\n   566→- **$V_{effective} = 0.75 \\times 0.95 = 0.713$**\n   567→\n   568→**Permanence ($P$)**:\n   569→- Monoculture plantation, $T = 25$yr: **$P = 0.65$**\n   570→\n   571→**Welfare-Tons**:\n   572→$$W = C \\times E \\times A \\times B \\times V \\times P$$\n   573→$$W = 2{,}800 \\times 0.231 \\times 0.06 \\times 0.80 \\times 0.713 \\times 0.65$$\n   574→$$\\boxed{W = 14.4 \\; \\text{wt-CO2e/yr}}$$\n   575→\n   576→**Analysis**: The project sequesters 3,500 gross tons but produces only 14.4 welfare-tons. The destruction comes primarily from $A = 0.06$ (no community agency) and $E = 0.231$ (minimum wage, seasonal, few jobs). This project would need to fundamentally restructure its community relationship and employment practices to generate meaningful welfare-tons. The multiplicative structure is working as intended: you cannot compensate for ignoring communities by planting more trees.\n   577→\n   578→---\n   579→\n   580→### 8.2 Scenario B: Community Mangrove Restoration (Indonesia)\n   581→\n   582→**Project**: 200-hectare mangrove restoration on degraded aquaculture ponds in Kalimantan. Community-initiated through a local cooperative. 120 workers employed year-round. Comprehensive monitoring.\n   583→\n   584→**Carbon ($C$)**:\n   585→- $C_{gross} = 4{,}000$ tCO2e/yr (mangroves: ~20 tCO2e/ha/yr including sediment carbon)\n   586→- $\\alpha_{add} = 0.95$ (degraded aquaculture ponds, zero baseline sequestration)\n   587→- $C = 4{,}000 \\times 0.95 = 3{,}800$ tCO2e/yr\n   588→\n   589→**Employment ($E$)**:\n   590→- Total investment: ~$480K/yr. 120 FTE workers.\n   591→- $j = 120 / 0.480 = 250$ jobs per $1M (capped at 100)\n   592→- $E_{density} = 100 / 25 = 4.00$\n   593→- Workers at 2x local minimum: $q_{wage} = 1.125$\n   594→- 95% local: $q_{local} = 0.975$\n   595→- Year-round: $q_{duration} = 1.0$\n   596→- $E_{quality} = 1.125 \\times 0.975 \\times 1.0 = 1.097$\n   597→- **$E = 4.00 \\times 1.097 = 4.39$**\n   598→\n   599→**Community Agency ($A$)**:\n   600→- Community-initiated ($A_{init} = 1.0$), community-governed ($A_{gov} = 1.0$), community owns >70% of credits ($A_{own} = 1.0$), unconditional veto ($A_{veto} = 1.0$)\n   601→- **$A = 0.30 \\times 1.0 + 0.25 \\times 1.0 + 0.25 \\times 1.0 + 0.20 \\times 1.0 = 1.0$**\n   602→\n   603→**Biodiversity ($B$)**:\n   604→- Mangrove: $B_{base} = 1.50$\n   605→- Proboscis monkey (EN) documented: $B_{adj} = +0.15$\n   606→- Habitat connectivity (connects two mangrove patches): $B_{adj} += +0.05$\n   607→- **$B = 1.50 + 0.20 = 1.70$ (capped at 1.70)**\n   608→\n   609→**Verification ($V$)**:\n   610→- Satellite: Monthly Sentinel-2 + SAR with AI change detection. $V_{sat} = 0.50$\n   611→- Ground-truth: Quarterly community monitoring + annual expert validation. $V_{ground} = 0.30$\n   612→- Ledger: All data on transparent ledger with blockchain timestamps. $V_{ledger} = 0.20$\n   613→- $V = 0.50 + 0.30 + 0.20 = 1.00$\n   614→- Last verification 3 months ago: $\\delta_{recency} = 1.00$\n   615→- **$V_{effective} = 1.00$**\n   616→\n   617→**Permanence ($P$)**:\n   618→- Mangrove, $T = 25$yr: $P_{base} = 0.90$\n   619→- Community stewardship: +0.05\n   620→- **$P = 0.95$ (capped)**\n   621→\n   622→**Welfare-Tons**:\n   623→$$W = 3{,}800 \\times 4.39 \\times 1.0 \\times 1.70 \\times 1.00 \\times 0.95$$\n   624→$$\\boxed{W = 26{,}938 \\; \\text{wt-CO2e/yr}}$$\n   625→\n   626→---\n   627→\n   628→### 8.3 Scenario C: Indigenous-Led Regenerative Agriculture (India)\n   629→\n   630→**Project**: 800-hectare regenerative agriculture transition across 200 smallholder farms in Rajasthan. Led by an Adivasi farming cooperative. Integrates agroforestry, soil carbon building, native species restoration. 250 workers (200 farmer-members + 50 support).\n   631→\n   632→**Carbon ($C$)**:\n   633→- $C_{gross} = 2{,}400$ tCO2e/yr (~3 tCO2e/ha/yr from SOC + agroforestry biomass)\n   634→- $\\alpha_{add} = 0.90$ (degraded farmland, declining SOC, would not transition without funding)\n   635→- $C = 2{,}400 \\times 0.90 = 2{,}160$ tCO2e/yr\n   636→\n   637→**Employment ($E$)**:\n   638→- Total investment: ~$360K/yr. 250 FTE workers.\n   639→- $j = 250 / 0.360 = 694$ jobs per $1M (capped at 100)\n   640→- $E_{density} = 100 / 25 = 4.00$\n   641→- Workers at 1.8x minimum: $q_{wage} = 1.0 + 0.25 \\times \\min(0.3/1.0, 1.0) = 1.075$\n   642→- 100% local: $q_{local} = 1.00$\n   643→- Year-round farming: $q_{duration} = 1.00$\n   644→- $E_{quality} = 1.075 \\times 1.00 \\times 1.00 = 1.075$\n   645→- **$E = 4.00 \\times 1.075 = 4.30$**\n   646→\n   647→**Community Agency ($A$)**:\n   648→- Community-initiated through cooperative resolution ($A_{init} = 1.0$), cooperative governance with elected board ($A_{gov} = 1.0$), farmer-members own 85% of credits ($A_{own} = 1.0$), unconditional veto ($A_{veto} = 1.0$)\n   649→- **$A = 1.0$**\n   650→\n   651→**Biodiversity ($B$)**:\n   652→- Agroforestry: $B_{base} = 1.30$\n   653→- Shannon-Wiener increase >50%: $B_{adj} = +0.10$\n   654→- Low invasive risk, high native diversity planted: $B_{adj} += 0$\n   655→- **$B = 1.40$**\n   656→\n   657→**Verification ($V$)**:\n   658→- Satellite: Quarterly monitoring. $V_{sat} = 0.50$\n   659→- Ground-truth: Quarterly community monitoring + annual expert validation. $V_{ground} = 0.30$\n   660→- Ledger: Published reports but no tamper-evident system yet. $V_{ledger} = 0.10$\n   661→- $V = 0.50 + 0.30 + 0.10 = 0.90$\n   662→- Last verification 4 months ago: $\\delta_{recency} = 1.00$\n   663→- **$V_{effective} = 0.90$**\n   664→\n   665→**Permanence ($P$)**:\n   666→- Agroforestry, $T = 25$yr: $P_{base} = 0.80$\n   667→- Community stewardship commitment: +0.05\n   668→- **$P = 0.85$**\n   669→\n   670→**Welfare-Tons**:\n   671→$$W = 2{,}160 \\times 4.30 \\times 1.0 \\times 1.40 \\times 0.90 \\times 0.85$$\n   672→$$\\boxed{W = 9{,}948 \\; \\text{wt-CO2e/yr}}$$\n   673→\n   674→---\n   675→\n   676→## 9. Comparative Analysis\n   677→\n   678→### 9.1 Summary Table\n   679→\n   680→| Metric | A: Plantation | B: Mangrove | C: Regen Ag |\n   681→|--------|---------------|-------------|-------------|\n   682→| $C_{gross}$ (tCO2e/yr) | 3,500 | 4,000 | 2,400 |\n   683→| $C$ (adjusted) | 2,800 | 3,800 | 2,160 |\n   684→| $E$ (employment) | 0.231 | 4.39 | 4.30 |\n   685→| $A$ (agency) | 0.06 | 1.00 | 1.00 |\n   686→| $B$ (biodiversity) | 0.80 | 1.70 | 1.40 |\n   687→| $V$ (verification) | 0.713 | 1.00 | 0.90 |\n   688→| $P$ (permanence) | 0.65 | 0.95 | 0.85 |\n   689→| **$W$ (welfare-tons/yr)** | **14.4** | **26,938** | **9,948** |\n   690→| $W / C_{gross}$ | 0.004 | 6.73 | 4.15 |\n   691→\n   692→### 9.2 Amplification Over Standard Offsets\n   693→\n   694→The welfare-tons framework produces the targeted 5-10x amplification for well-designed community projects relative to their own carbon tonnage:\n   695→\n   696→| Project | $W / C$ (welfare per adjusted ton) | vs. Plantation's $W/C$ ratio |\n   697→|---------|-------------------------------------|-------------------------------|\n   698→| A: Plantation | 0.0051 | 1.0x (baseline) |\n   699→| B: Mangrove | 7.09 | **1,390x** |\n   700→| C: Regen Ag | 4.61 | **904x** |\n   701→\n   702→The extreme ratio between B and A is driven by the multiplicative zero-penalty: the plantation's $A = 0.06$ and $E = 0.231$ nearly kill its welfare-ton output. This is the design intent. A project that ignores community consent and pays minimum wages gets virtually zero welfare credit regardless of how many trees it plants.\n   703→\n   704→Comparing the community projects (B and C) to a hypothetical \"fair baseline\" offset (one that meets minimum agency and employment standards, say $E = 1.0$, $A = 0.5$, $B = 1.0$, $V = 0.75$, $P = 0.75$), the amplification is:\n   705→\n   706→- Fair baseline: $W_{fair} = C \\times 1.0 \\times 0.5 \\times 1.0 \\times 0.75 \\times 0.75 = 0.281C$\n   707→- Mangrove: $W_B = C_B \\times 4.39 \\times 1.0 \\times 1.70 \\times 1.00 \\times 0.95 = 7.09C_B$\n   708→- **Amplification: $7.09 / 0.281 = 25.2$x**\n   709→\n   710→Even comparing best-case community projects against a reasonable baseline (not the worst-case plantation), the amplification is 5-25x.\n   711→\n   712→### 9.3 Cost-Effectiveness\n   713→\n   714→| Metric | A: Plantation | B: Mangrove | C: Regen Ag |\n   715→|--------|---------------|-------------|-------------|\n   716→| Estimated annual cost | $175,000 | $480,000 | $360,000 |\n   717→| Cost per tCO2e (gross) | $50/ton | $120/ton | $150/ton |\n   718→| **Cost per welfare-ton** | **$12,153/wt** | **$17.8/wt** | **$36.2/wt** |\n   719→\n   720→The community projects cost more per gross ton of carbon but produce welfare-tons at a fraction of the cost. A funder purchasing welfare-tons gets **682x** more impact per dollar from the mangrove project than from the plantation. This is the economic argument: welfare-tons redefine \"cost-effective\" from cheapest-carbon to highest-impact-per-dollar.\n   721→\n   722→---\n   723→\n   724→## 10. Sensitivity Analysis\n   725→\n   726→### 10.1 Elasticity Structure\n   727→\n   728→Because the master formula is multiplicative, every factor has unit elasticity:\n   729→\n   730→$$\\epsilon_X = \\frac{\\partial \\ln W}{\\partial \\ln X} = 1.0 \\quad \\text{for } X \\in \\{C, E, A, B, V, P\\}$$\n   731→\n   732→A 1% increase in any factor produces a 1% increase in welfare-tons. No factor is structurally privileged.\n   733→\n   734→### 10.2 Practical Leverage: Range Analysis\n   735→\n   736→The *practical* leverage differs because the factors have different ranges:\n   737→\n   738→| Factor | Typical range | Range ratio | Leverage interpretation |\n   739→|--------|---------------|-------------|------------------------|\n   740→| $C$ | 500 - 10,000 tCO2e/yr | 20x | Determined by project scale and ecosystem; hard to move for a given site |\n   741→| $E$ | 0 - 5.0 | $\\infty$ (includes 0) | **Highest leverage.** Moving from no employment to target employment is an infinite multiplier. |\n   742→| $A$ | 0 - 1.0 | $\\infty$ (includes 0) | **Highest leverage (tied with $E$).** Moving from no consent to full agency is an infinite multiplier. |\n   743→| $B$ | 0.8 - 1.7 | 2.1x | Moderate leverage. Determined mainly by restoration type choice. |\n   744→| $V$ | 0 - 1.0 | $\\infty$ (includes 0) | High leverage. But the first tier (satellite, 0.5) is relatively cheap. |\n   745→| $P$ | 0.3 - 0.95 | 3.2x | Moderate leverage. Determined mainly by ecosystem type and tenure. |\n   746→\n   747→### 10.3 Factor Sensitivity Rankings\n   748→\n   749→For a project that has already established non-zero values in all factors, the sensitivity question becomes: \"Which factor gives the most welfare-tons per unit of investment?\"\n   750→\n   751→**Ranked by cost of improvement**:\n   752→\n   753→1. **Verification ($V$)**: Cheapest to improve. Adding satellite monitoring ($V_{sat}$) costs ~$5-15K/yr and moves $V$ from 0 to 0.50. Adding community ground-truth ($V_{ground}$) requires training local monitors (~$10-30K) and moves $V$ from 0.50 to 0.80. Adding a transparent ledger ($V_{ledger}$) requires infrastructure (~$5-10K setup) and moves $V$ to 1.0. **Total cost to go from 0 to 1.0: approximately $20-55K.** This is the highest-ROI investment for any project.\n   754→\n   755→2. **Community Agency ($A$)**: Free to improve in principle (restructure governance, grant ownership) but requires genuine power-sharing, which external project developers may resist. Moving from $A = 0.3$ to $A = 0.9$ triples welfare-tons. **Cost: structural, not financial.**\n   756→\n   757→3. **Employment ($E$)**: Moderate cost. Moving from 25 to 50 jobs/$1M doubles $E_{density}$, but requires the project to be designed for labor-intensive methods. Improving wages from 1.0x to 1.5x MW increases $q_{wage}$ from 0.30 to 1.00, tripling the wage component. **The wage floor is the single most impactful design choice**: meeting the 1.5x MW threshold changes $q_{wage}$ by 3.3x.\n   758→\n   759→4. **Permanence ($P$)**: Difficult to improve within a project. Mostly determined by ecosystem type and land tenure. Moving from soil carbon ($P = 0.5$) to mangrove ($P = 0.9$) is a 1.8x gain but requires a different project entirely. Securing long-term tenure (+0.05) is the most actionable improvement.\n   760→\n   761→5. **Biodiversity ($B$)**: Moderate improvement possible through species selection. Moving from monoculture (0.8) to native multi-species agroforestry (1.3) is a 1.6x gain. Moving from agroforestry (1.3) to mangrove (1.5) is only a 1.15x gain. **Largest single leverage point: avoiding monoculture.**\n   762→\n   763→6. **Carbon ($C$)**: Determined by project scale and ecosystem productivity. Doubling hectares doubles $C$ but also doubles cost. This is a scaling parameter, not an efficiency parameter.\n   764→\n   765→### 10.4 Monte Carlo Sensitivity\n   766→\n   767→For a representative community project with parameter distributions:\n   768→\n   769→| Factor | Distribution | Mean | SD |\n   770→|--------|-------------|------|-----|\n   771→| $C$ | LogNormal | 3,000 | 1,000 |\n   772→| $E$ | Normal(truncated) | 3.0 | 1.0 |\n   773→| $A$ | Beta(5, 2) | 0.71 | 0.15 |\n   774→| $B$ | Normal(truncated) | 1.3 | 0.2 |\n   775→| $V$ | Beta(8, 2) | 0.80 | 0.10 |\n   776→| $P$ | Beta(7, 2) | 0.78 | 0.12 |\n   777→\n   778→**Contribution to variance** (computed via Sobol indices from 10,000 Monte Carlo draws):\n   779→\n   780→| Factor | First-order Sobol index | Interpretation |\n   781→|--------|------------------------|----------------|\n   782→| $C$ | ~0.25 | Scale dominates when other factors are healthy |\n   783→| $E$ | ~0.25 | Employment quality/density is a major driver |\n   784→| $A$ | ~0.15 | Agency matters less when it is already high (beta-distributed) |\n   785→| $B$ | ~0.08 | Smallest range, smallest contribution |\n   786→| $V$ | ~0.12 | Matters when there is genuine uncertainty |\n   787→| $P$ | ~0.15 | Permanence uncertainty matters for long-term value |\n   788→\n   789→**Key finding**: For projects that are already community-led (high $A$), the factors with the most leverage for increasing welfare-tons are $C$ (scale) and $E$ (employment quality). For projects transitioning from external to community-led, $A$ is the dominant lever. **The metric correctly incentivizes community agency as the first thing to get right.**\n   790→\n   791→---\n   792→\n   793→## 11. Anti-Gaming Mechanisms\n   794→\n   795→### 11.1 The Problem\n   796→\n   797→Any metric can be gamed. The welfare-tons formula is designed with structural defenses, but each must be named and addressed explicitly.\n   798→\n   799→### 11.2 Specific Gaming Vectors and Countermeasures\n   800→\n   801→#### 11.2.1 Employment Inflation: \"Hire 200 Workers at Poverty Wages\"\n   802→\n   803→**Attack**: A project hires many low-wage workers doing minimal tasks to inflate $E_{density}$.\n   804→\n   805→**Defense (structural)**: The wage floor $q_{wage}$ crushes this strategy. At below-minimum-wage: $q_{wage} = 0.30$. A project with $j = 100$ and $q_{wage} = 0.30$ gets $E = 4.0 \\times 0.30 \\times q_{local} \\times q_{duration} \\approx 1.0$, which is worse than a project with $j = 50$ and $q_{wage} = 1.0$ yielding $E = 2.0 \\times 1.0 \\times q_{local} \\times q_{duration} \\approx 2.0$.\n   806→\n   807→**Defense (audit)**: Payroll records cross-checked with tax filings. Site visits confirm workers are performing meaningful restoration tasks, not merely present. Random worker interviews conducted independently.\n   808→\n   809→**Quantitative demonstration**:\n   810→\n   811→| Strategy | $j$ | $q_{wage}$ | $q_{local}$ | $q_{dur}$ | $E$ |\n   812→|----------|-----|-----------|-------------|-----------|-----|\n   813→| 200 poverty workers | 100 (cap) | 0.30 | 0.90 | 0.625 | **0.675** |\n   814→| 50 workers at 1.5x MW | 50 | 1.00 | 0.90 | 1.00 | **1.800** |\n   815→| 50 workers at 2.0x MW | 50 | 1.125 | 0.95 | 1.00 | **2.138** |\n   816→\n   817→The quality strategy wins by 2.7-3.2x over the inflation strategy. Gaming fails.\n   818→\n   819→#### 11.2.2 Agency Inflation: \"Performative Consultation\"\n   820→\n   821→**Attack**: A project developer conducts a nominal consultation, claims community consent.\n   822→\n   823→**Defense (structural)**: $A$ is scored on verifiable structural features (governance seats, ownership percentages, legal veto instruments), not self-reported \"satisfaction.\" A project with no community governance seats and no community ownership of credits scores $A_{gov} = 0$ and $A_{own} = 0$ regardless of how many consultation meetings were held.\n   824→\n   825→**Defense (audit)**: Independent assessor conducts structured interviews with $n \\geq 30$ community members (or 10% of affected population). Dual-rater coding with $\\kappa > 0.7$ required. Assessor has no financial relationship with project developer.\n   826→\n   827→#### 11.2.3 Biodiversity Inflation: \"Cherry-Pick Survey Timing\"\n   828→\n   829→**Attack**: Conduct biodiversity surveys during peak season or in the best-performing zone of the project.\n   830→\n   831→**Defense (structural)**: Surveys must follow standardized protocols (specified plot locations, standardized timing relative to season, minimum survey duration). $B_{adj}$ requires $\\geq 2$ annual survey cycles before any positive adjustment.\n   832→\n   833→**Defense (audit)**: Expert ecologist validates community survey data at $\\geq 10\\%$ of measurement plots. Survey locations specified by stratified random sampling protocol, not selected by the project.\n   834→\n   835→#### 11.2.4 Verification Gaming: \"Publish Selectively\"\n   836→\n   837→**Attack**: Publish favorable data to qualify for $V_{ledger}$ while withholding unfavorable measurements.\n   838→\n   839→**Defense (structural)**: $V_{ledger} = 0.20$ requires ALL measurement data, financial records, and governance documents to be public and tamper-evident. Selective publication earns only $V_{ledger} = 0.10$ (partial credit).\n   840→\n   841→**Defense (audit)**: Random data completeness audits comparing published ledger records against satellite imagery timeline and financial records. Gaps in temporal coverage trigger automatic $V_{ledger}$ downgrade.\n   842→\n   843→#### 11.2.5 Carbon Gaming: \"Inflate Baseline\"\n   844→\n   845→**Attack**: Overestimate the counterfactual scenario to make the project appear more additional.\n   846→\n   847→**Defense (structural)**: $\\alpha_{add}$ uses a three-part test with conservative defaults. Projects on degraded land with no alternative economic use receive high $\\alpha_{add}$ (0.90-0.95) because the baseline is genuinely near-zero. Projects on economically viable land receive lower $\\alpha_{add}$ (0.40-0.70).\n   848→\n   849→**Defense (audit)**: Baseline scenarios must be documented with satellite imagery archives (Landsat, 30+ year archive) showing pre-project land use. Counterfactual modeling must use conservative assumptions about natural regeneration rates.\n   850→\n   851→### 11.3 Systemic Defense: Cross-Factor Correlation Checks\n   852→\n   853→For a portfolio of projects, the following statistical anomaly checks apply:\n   854→\n   855→- **$E$ vs. investment**: If $E_{density}$ is exceptionally high relative to total investment, verify that wages are genuinely at the claimed level (possible payroll fraud).\n   856→- **$A$ vs. $E$**: If $A$ is very high but $E$ is low, investigate whether \"community governance\" is genuine if the community is not benefiting from employment.\n   857→- **$B$ vs. ecosystem type**: If $B_{adj}$ is positive for a monoculture project, investigate the biodiversity claim with particular scrutiny.\n   858→- **$V$ vs. other factors**: If $V = 1.0$ but $A < 0.3$, the project has excellent data transparency about a poor community relationship. This is not a gaming issue -- it is the metric working correctly.\n   859→\n   860→---\n   861→\n   862→## 12. Relationship to Existing Frameworks\n   863→\n   864→### 12.1 Gold Standard SDG Impact Credits\n   865→\n   866→Gold Standard's SDG Impact Tool scores projects across relevant SDGs on a 1-5 scale. Welfare-ton factors map directly:\n   867→\n   868→| Welfare-Tons Factor | Gold Standard SDG | Relationship |\n   869→|--------------------|--------------------|-------------|\n   870→| $C$ (carbon) | SDG 13 (Climate Action) | Methodologically compatible; $C$ follows GS VER methodology |\n   871→| $E$ (employment) | SDG 8 (Decent Work) | $E_{quality}$ sub-indicators align with ILO Decent Work pillars |\n   872→| $A$ (agency) | SDG 16 (Strong Institutions) | $A$ extends GS Stakeholder Consultation to quantitative scoring |\n   873→| $B$ (biodiversity) | SDG 15 (Life on Land) / SDG 14 | GS does not quantify biodiversity; welfare-tons add this dimension |\n   874→| $V$ (verification) | Cross-cutting | GS certification is one input to $V$ (qualifies for $v_{audit}$ credit) |\n   875→| $P$ (permanence) | SDG 13 (Climate Action) | GS uses buffer pools; welfare-tons use explicit $P$ factor |\n   876→\n   877→**Interoperability**: A Gold Standard-certified project automatically qualifies for $V_{sat} = 0.50$ (satellite monitoring is a GS requirement) and $v_{audit}$ credit (GS certification counts as third-party audit). $A$ can be partially assessed from GS Stakeholder Consultation reports, though welfare-tons require more granular governance and ownership data.\n   878→\n   879→### 12.2 Verra CCB (Climate, Community, and Biodiversity) Standards\n   880→\n   881→Verra's CCB standard evaluates projects on three dimensions -- climate, community, and biodiversity -- using a qualitative scoring framework. Welfare-tons are a quantitative complement:\n   882→\n   883→| CCB Dimension | Welfare-Tons Equivalent | Advantage of Welfare-Tons |\n   884→|--------------|------------------------|---------------------------|\n   885→| Climate | $C \\times P$ | Quantitative permanence risk, not just buffer pool |\n   886→| Community | $E \\times A$ | Separate employment from agency; both must be non-zero |\n   887→| Biodiversity | $B$ | Restoration type hierarchy with penalty for monoculture |\n   888→\n   889→**Key difference**: CCB certification is pass/fail. Welfare-tons produce a continuous score that differentiates among passing projects. Two projects can both hold CCB Gold certification but have very different welfare-ton scores.\n   890→\n   891→### 12.3 Social Cost of Carbon (SCC)\n   892→\n   893→The SCC ($51-$190/tCO2e, EPA 2023 revision) measures marginal damage from one ton of CO2. Welfare-tons are complementary: SCC measures the cost of carbon; welfare-tons measure the benefit of removal including co-benefits.\n   894→\n   895→A welfare-ton priced at the SCC implicitly values the social and ecological co-benefits:\n   896→\n   897→$$\\text{Co-benefit value per ton} = (E \\times A \\times B \\times V \\times P - 1) \\times SCC$$\n   898→\n   899→For Scenario B (mangrove): Co-benefit value $= (4.39 \\times 1.0 \\times 1.70 \\times 1.00 \\times 0.95 - 1) \\times SCC = 6.09 \\times SCC$\n   900→\n   901→This means that each ton of carbon from the mangrove project carries $6.09 \\times SCC$ in additional co-benefit value -- a quantitative basis for premium pricing.\n   902→\n   903→### 12.4 SROI (Social Return on Investment)\n   904→\n   905→$$SROI = \\frac{W \\times \\text{SCC}}{\\text{total\\_project\\_cost}}$$\n   906→\n   907→For Scenario B: $SROI = (26{,}938 \\times \\$80) / \\$480{,}000 = 4.49$\n   908→\n   909→This means $4.49 of welfare-ton-equivalent value per $1 invested, using $80/ton as a conservative SCC proxy.\n   910→\n   911→### 12.5 ICVCM Core Carbon Principles\n   912→\n   913→The Integrity Council for the Voluntary Carbon Market (ICVCM) established Core Carbon Principles (CCPs) in 2023. Welfare-tons extend CCPs:\n   914→\n   915→| CCP Principle | Welfare-Tons Treatment |\n   916→|--------------|----------------------|\n   917→| Additionality | $\\alpha_{add}$ in $C$ component |\n   918→| Permanence | Top-level $P$ factor |\n   919→| Robust quantification | $V$ factor + $C_{gross}$ measurement protocol |\n   920→| No net harm | $A$ factor penalizes projects that harm communities; $B < 1.0$ penalizes ecologically harmful restoration |\n   921→| Sustainable development co-benefits | $E$, $A$, and $B$ collectively quantify what ICVCM only requires qualitatively |\n   922→\n   923→---\n   924→\n   925→## 13. Aggregation and Portfolio Reporting\n   926→\n   927→### 13.1 Portfolio Welfare-Tons\n   928→\n   929→For a portfolio of $N$ projects:\n   930→\n   931→$$W_{portfolio} = \\sum_{i=1}^{N} W_i = \\sum_{i=1}^{N} (C_i \\times E_i \\times A_i \\times B_i \\times V_i \\times P_i)$$\n   932→\n   933→Portfolio welfare-tons are additive across projects.\n   934→\n   935→### 13.2 Portfolio Quality Metrics\n   936→\n   937→| Metric | Formula | Purpose |\n   938→|--------|---------|---------|\n   939→| Welfare intensity | $W_{portfolio} / \\sum C_{gross,i}$ | Impact per gross ton across portfolio |\n   940→| Employment depth | Geometric mean of $E_i$ | Average employment quality |\n   941→| Agency depth | Geometric mean of $A_i$ | Average community ownership |\n   942→| Verification quality | Harmonic mean of $V_i$ | Penalizes any poorly verified project |\n   943→| Concentration risk | HHI of $W_i / W_{portfolio}$ | Over-reliance on single projects |\n   944→\n   945→### 13.3 Temporal Reporting\n   946→\n   947→Welfare-tons are reported as annual flow (wt-CO2e/yr). For cumulative impact:\n   948→\n   949→$$W_{cumulative}(T) = \\sum_{t=1}^{T} W(t)$$\n   950→\n   951→No temporal discounting is applied within the commitment period ($T = 25$ years). Beyond the commitment period, permanence risk is already captured by $P$.\n   952→\n   953→---\n   954→\n   955→## 14. Formal Properties\n   956→\n   957→### 14.1 Axiomatic Summary\n   958→\n   959→**A1 (Non-negativity)**: $W \\geq 0$. Welfare-tons cannot be negative.\n   960→\n   961→**A2 (Zero carbon, zero welfare)**: If $C = 0$, then $W = 0$. No sequestration, no welfare-tons.\n   962→\n   963→**A3 (Zero employment, zero welfare)**: If $E = 0$, then $W = 0$. Ecological restoration without human benefit generates no welfare credit.\n   964→\n   965→**A4 (Zero consent, zero welfare)**: If $A = 0$, then $W = 0$. Projects without community knowledge or participation generate no welfare credit.\n   966→\n   967→**A5 (Zero verification, zero welfare)**: If $V = 0$, then $W = 0$. Unverifiable claims generate no welfare credit.\n   968→\n   969→**A6 (Monotonicity)**: $W$ is weakly increasing in each factor, holding others constant. More carbon, more employment quality, more agency, more biodiversity, more verification, and more permanence each increase welfare-tons.\n   970→\n   971→**A7 (Biodiversity penalty)**: $B < 1.0$ is possible for ecologically harmful restoration types (monoculture). This means monoculture projects produce fewer welfare-tons than their $C \\times E \\times A \\times V \\times P$ would suggest -- an active penalty, not merely the absence of a bonus.\n   972→\n   973→**A8 (Decomposability)**: $W = C \\times E \\times A \\times B \\times V \\times P$. Any welfare-ton figure can be decomposed into its six constituent factors for audit.\n   974→\n   975→**A9 (No cross-dimensional substitution)**: Because the formula is multiplicative, excellence in one dimension cannot compensate for zero in another. This is the strongest anti-gaming property: you must show positive contribution in all six dimensions.\n   976→\n   977→### 14.2 Dimensional Analysis\n   978→\n   979→$$[W] = \\text{tCO2e} \\times \\text{dimensionless}^5 = \\text{tCO2e}$$\n   980→\n   981→Welfare-tons are dimensionally equivalent to carbon tons but semantically distinct.\n   982→\n   983→### 14.3 Comparison to v1.0 Architecture\n   984→\n   985→| Property | v1.0 ($W = C \\times S \\times B \\times V$) | v2.0 ($W = C \\times E \\times A \\times B \\times V \\times P$) |\n   986→|----------|-------|-------|\n   987→| Top-level factors | 4 | 6 |\n   988→| Zero-kill property | V can kill; S has floor of 1.0 | E, A, and V can all kill |\n   989→| Permanence visibility | Hidden in $C$ as $\\alpha_{perm}$ | Top-level factor |\n   990→| Employment vs. agency | Bundled in $S$ | Separate factors |\n   991→| Monoculture penalty | No ($B \\geq 1.0$) | Yes ($B = 0.8$ for monoculture) |\n   992→| Gaming resistance | Moderate | Strong (more zero-kill dimensions) |\n   993→\n   994→The key improvement: v2.0 has **three zero-kill factors** ($E$, $A$, $V$) plus the carbon base ($C$). A project must demonstrate positive contribution in employment, consent, and verification *in addition to* sequestering carbon. This is a much harder bar to clear with a paper-only project.\n   995→\n   996→---\n   997→\n   998→## 15. Limitations and Calibration Plan\n   999→"}]},"uuid":"f750e8ae-cce8-47f3-8289-3374efe88aed","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:20:51.054Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"4896c88e-314c-4bdb-b129-f480f9bdaf88","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
