{"parentUuid":"3b3b62bd-98eb-4ebf-a61c-9155b157aca4","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"bash \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/hooks/run-with-flags-shell.sh\" \"post:observe\" \"skills/continuous-learning-v2/hooks/observe.sh\" \"standard,strict\""},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_017AzyK2d3iLXmQYtwTnZArB","toolUseID":"toolu_017AzyK2d3iLXmQYtwTnZArB","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:21:05.061Z","uuid":"a9e0dfc1-cbab-457a-9503-43e9f907a86c","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"a9e0dfc1-cbab-457a-9503-43e9f907a86c","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_017AzyK2d3iLXmQYtwTnZArB","toolUseID":"toolu_017AzyK2d3iLXmQYtwTnZArB","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:21:05.061Z","uuid":"3be8daf7-a896-43e5-8d81-2af8c0f3c887","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"04a9e506-ba77-4b50-b3c2-27e6858e53d3","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"3cfdca64-d5a0-407a-b98d-81d58c820453","agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017AzyK2d3iLXmQYtwTnZArB","type":"tool_result","content":"   999→\n  1000→### 15.1 Known Limitations\n  1001→\n  1002→**L1: Extreme sensitivity to $A$ near zero.** The multiplicative structure means that $A = 0.06$ (Scenario A) decimates welfare-tons. This is intentional but may be perceived as harsh by developers of projects that genuinely benefit communities but have not formalized governance structures. *Mitigation*: Provide clear guidance on minimum $A$ requirements and support projects in formalizing community governance before scoring.\n  1003→\n  1004→**L2: $E_{density}$ cap is a blunt instrument.** Capping at 100 jobs/$1M prevents extreme values but may penalize genuinely labor-intensive smallholder projects where investment per job is very low. *Mitigation*: The cap is set high enough (100 jobs/$1M) that it only binds for projects with very low capital intensity. Most restoration projects fall well below this threshold. Revisit after pilot data.\n  1005→\n  1006→**L3: PPP adjustment complexity.** Cross-country wage comparisons require PPP adjustment, which introduces measurement uncertainty and can lag reality in volatile economies. *Mitigation*: Use World Bank PPP data, updated annually. For countries with >20% annual inflation, use quarterly PPP adjustments if available.\n  1007→\n  1008→**L4: Biodiversity survey cost.** The $B_{adj}$ adjustment requires standardized biodiversity surveys that are expensive in remote areas. Without surveys, $B_{adj} = 0$ and the project receives only the base score. *Mitigation*: Fund baseline surveys as a system cost, not a project cost. Train community monitors to conduct standardized surveys at lower cost.\n  1009→\n  1010→**L5: Permanence for novel ecosystems.** $P$ defaults are based on established ecosystem types. Novel or hybrid restoration approaches (e.g., blue carbon in combination with aquaculture) may not fit neatly into the table. *Mitigation*: Use the closest analogue as the starting point and flag for expert assessment.\n  1011→\n  1012→**L6: Interaction effects not captured.** The multiplicative structure treats factors as independent, but in reality they interact: community agency ($A$) likely increases permanence ($P$) through stewardship, and employment ($E$) likely increases verification quality ($V$) through community monitoring. The current formula does not capture these synergies. *Mitigation*: Document interaction hypotheses. Test with pilot data. Consider adding interaction terms in v3.0 if empirically supported.\n  1013→\n  1014→### 15.2 Calibration Plan (Pilot Phase)\n  1015→\n  1016→During the first 3-5 pilot projects:\n  1017→\n  1018→1. **Weight sensitivity**: Compute welfare-tons under alternative $B$ hierarchies (e.g., narrower or wider ranges). Report rank correlation between projects. If ranking is unstable (Kendall's $\\tau < 0.7$), revise the hierarchy.\n  1019→\n  1020→2. **Inter-rater reliability**: Have 3 independent assessment teams score the same 3 projects on $A$. Compute ICC(2,k). Sub-dimensions with ICC $< 0.6$ are flagged for protocol revision.\n  1021→\n  1022→3. **Wage floor calibration**: Verify that 1.5x MW is achievable and meaningful across pilot geographies. Adjust if the floor is too low (meaningless) or too high (excludes viable projects) in specific regions.\n  1023→\n  1024→4. **Community feedback**: Present welfare-ton scores and decomposition to community stakeholders. Ask: \"Does this number capture what you think is most valuable about this project?\" Adjust sub-indicator weights based on systematic community input.\n  1025→\n  1026→5. **Cross-validation against SROI**: Commission independent SROI assessments for pilot projects. Compare welfare-ton rankings with SROI rankings. Investigate divergences.\n  1027→\n  1028→### 15.3 Version Roadmap\n  1029→\n  1030→| Version | Target | Key Changes |\n  1031→|---------|--------|-------------|\n  1032→| 2.0 (this document) | Specification | 6-factor flat formula, anti-gaming, sensitivity analysis |\n  1033→| 2.1 (post-pilot) | Calibrated | $B$ hierarchy and $E$ cap refined from pilot data; ICC-tested $A$ rubric |\n  1034→| 2.2 | Temporal dynamics | Project maturation curves (young projects score differently) |\n  1035→| 3.0 | Full standard | Independently auditable standard; accredited assessors; interaction terms |\n  1036→| 3.1 | Market integration | Welfare-ton pricing framework for voluntary carbon market integration |\n  1037→\n  1038→---\n  1039→\n  1040→## 16. Glossary\n  1041→\n  1042→| Term | Definition |\n  1043→|------|------------|\n  1044→| wt-CO2e | Welfare-ton of CO2-equivalent. The unit of the welfare-tons metric. |\n  1045→| tCO2e | Metric ton of CO2-equivalent. Standard carbon accounting unit. |\n  1046→| $C_{gross}$ | Total measured carbon sequestration before additionality adjustment. |\n  1047→| $\\alpha_{add}$ | Additionality discount factor, reflecting the counterfactual baseline. |\n  1048→| $E_{density}$ | Jobs per $1M invested, normalized against reference (25 jobs/$1M). |\n  1049→| $E_{quality}$ | Composite of wage quality, local labor fraction, and employment duration. |\n  1050→| $q_{wage}$ | Wage quality sub-score. Floor at 1.5x minimum wage for full credit. |\n  1051→| FPIC | Free, Prior, and Informed Consent. Foundation of $A$ factor. |\n  1052→| $B_{base}$ | Default biodiversity score by restoration type, from peer-reviewed hierarchy. |\n  1053→| $B_{adj}$ | Project-specific biodiversity adjustment ($\\pm 0.2$ from base). |\n  1054→| $V_{sat}$ | Verification credit for systematic satellite monitoring. |\n  1055→| $V_{ground}$ | Verification credit for community ground-truth data collection. |\n  1056→| $V_{ledger}$ | Verification credit for transparent, tamper-evident data publication. |\n  1057→| $P_{reversal}$ | Estimated probability of >25% carbon stock reversal over horizon $T$. |\n  1058→| SCC | Social Cost of Carbon. Estimated marginal damage from one ton of CO2. |\n  1059→| SROI | Social Return on Investment. Total value created per dollar invested. |\n  1060→| PPP | Purchasing Power Parity. Exchange rate adjustment for cost-of-living. |\n  1061→| HHI | Herfindahl-Hirschman Index. Concentration measure. |\n  1062→| ICC | Intraclass Correlation Coefficient. Inter-rater reliability measure. |\n  1063→| ICVCM | Integrity Council for the Voluntary Carbon Market. |\n  1064→| CCB | Climate, Community, and Biodiversity (Verra standard). |\n  1065→\n  1066→---\n  1067→\n  1068→## 17. References\n  1069→\n  1070→Barbier, E.B. (2016). The protective service of mangrove ecosystems: A review of valuation methods. *Marine Pollution Bulletin*, 109(2), 676-681.\n  1071→\n  1072→Bhagwat, S.A., Willis, K.J., Birks, H.J.B., & Whittaker, R.J. (2008). Agroforestry: A refuge for tropical biodiversity? *Trends in Ecology & Evolution*, 23(5), 261-267.\n  1073→\n  1074→Brockerhoff, E.G., Jactel, H., Parrotta, J.A., Quine, C.P., & Sayer, J. (2008). Plantation forests and biodiversity: Oxymoron or opportunity? *Biodiversity and Conservation*, 17, 925-951.\n  1075→\n  1076→Chave, J., et al. (2014). Improved allometric models to estimate the aboveground biomass of tropical trees. *Global Change Biology*, 20(10), 3177-3190.\n  1077→\n  1078→Crouzeilles, R., et al. (2016). A global meta-analysis on the ecological drivers of forest restoration success. *Nature Communications*, 7, 11666.\n  1079→\n  1080→Donato, D.C., et al. (2011). Mangroves among the most carbon-rich forests in the tropics. *Nature Geoscience*, 4(5), 293-297.\n  1081→\n  1082→Gann, G.D., et al. (2019). International principles and standards for the practice of ecological restoration. *Restoration Ecology*, 27(S1), S1-S46.\n  1083→\n  1084→Gold Standard. (2019). *Gold Standard for the Global Goals: SDG Impact Tool*. Geneva: Gold Standard Foundation.\n  1085→\n  1086→ILO. (2015). *Guidelines for a just transition towards environmentally sustainable economies and societies for all*. Geneva: International Labour Organization.\n  1087→\n  1088→IPCC. (2022). *Climate Change 2022: Mitigation of Climate Change*. Working Group III Contribution to the Sixth Assessment Report.\n  1089→\n  1090→Lewis, S.L., Wheeler, C.E., Mitchard, E.T.A., & Koch, A. (2019). Restoring natural forests is the best way to remove atmospheric carbon. *Nature*, 568, 25-28.\n  1091→\n  1092→Nagelkerken, I., et al. (2008). The habitat function of mangroves for terrestrial and marine fauna: A review. *Aquatic Botany*, 89(2), 155-185.\n  1093→\n  1094→Pearson, T.R.H., Walker, S., & Brown, S. (2007). *Sourcebook for Land Use, Land-Use Change and Forestry Projects*. Washington: BioCarbon Fund, World Bank.\n  1095→\n  1096→Saura, S., & Pascual-Hortal, L. (2007). A new habitat availability index to integrate connectivity in landscape conservation planning. *Landscape Ecology*, 22(6), 811-823.\n  1097→\n  1098→Seddon, N., et al. (2020). Understanding the value and limits of nature-based solutions to climate change. *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B*, 375(1794), 20190120.\n  1099→\n  1100→Unsworth, R.K.F., et al. (2019). Global challenges for seagrass conservation. *Ambio*, 48, 801-815.\n  1101→\n  1102→US EPA. (2023). *Supplementary Material for the Regulatory Impact Analysis: EPA's Updated Social Cost of Greenhouse Gases*. EPA-HQ-OAR-2023-0072.\n  1103→\n  1104→---\n  1105→\n  1106→## Appendix A: Quick-Reference Calculation Worksheet\n  1107→\n  1108→```\n  1109→PROJECT NAME: _______________\n  1110→DATE: _______________\n  1111→ASSESSOR: _______________\n  1112→\n  1113→STEP 1: CARBON (C)\n  1114→  C_gross (tCO2e/yr):            ___________\n  1115→  alpha_add (Sec 2.3):           ___________\n  1116→  C = C_gross * alpha_add:       ___________\n  1117→\n  1118→STEP 2: EMPLOYMENT (E)\n  1119→  Total investment ($M):         ___________\n  1120→  FTE jobs created:              ___________\n  1121→  j = jobs / investment:         ___________\n  1122→  E_density = min(j,100) / 25:  ___________\n  1123→  Avg wage / min wage:           ___________\n  1124→  q_wage (Sec 3.3.1):           ___________\n  1125→  Fraction local workers:        ___________\n  1126→  q_local (Sec 3.3.2):          ___________\n  1127→  Avg contract months:           ___________\n  1128→  q_duration (Sec 3.3.3):       ___________\n  1129→  E_quality = q_wage * q_local * q_duration: ___________\n  1130→  E = E_density * E_quality:     ___________\n  1131→\n  1132→STEP 3: COMMUNITY AGENCY (A)\n  1133→  A_init (0-1, Sec 4.2.1):      ___________\n  1134→  A_gov (0-1, Sec 4.2.2):       ___________\n  1135→  A_own (0-1, Sec 4.2.3):       ___________\n  1136→  A_veto (0-1, Sec 4.2.4):      ___________\n  1137→  A = 0.30*A_init + 0.25*A_gov + 0.25*A_own + 0.20*A_veto: ___________\n  1138→\n  1139→STEP 4: BIODIVERSITY (B)\n  1140→  Restoration type:              ___________\n  1141→  B_base (Table, Sec 5.2):      ___________\n  1142→  B_adj (Sec 5.3):              ___________\n  1143→  B = B_base + B_adj:           ___________\n  1144→\n  1145→STEP 5: VERIFICATION (V)\n  1146→  V_sat (0 or 0.50):            ___________\n  1147→  V_ground (0, 0.15, or 0.30): ___________\n  1148→  V_ledger (0, 0.10, or 0.20): ___________\n  1149→  V = V_sat + V_ground + V_ledger: ___________\n  1150→  Months since last verification: ___________\n  1151→  delta_recency (Sec 6.4):      ___________\n  1152→  V_effective = V * delta_recency: ___________\n  1153→\n  1154→STEP 6: PERMANENCE (P)\n  1155→  Ecosystem type:                ___________\n  1156→  P_base (Table, Sec 7.2):      ___________\n  1157→  Adjustments (Sec 7.3):        ___________\n  1158→  P = P_base + adjustments:     ___________\n  1159→\n  1160→STEP 7: WELFARE-TONS (W)\n  1161→  W = C * E * A * B * V_eff * P: ___________\n  1162→\n  1163→DECOMPOSITION:\n  1164→  Carbon efficiency:  C / C_gross =  _____ (additionality)\n  1165→  Employment factor:  E =            _____ (job quality)\n  1166→  Community agency:   A =            _____ (consent & ownership)\n  1167→  Biodiversity:       B =            _____ (ecosystem quality)\n  1168→  Verification:       V_eff =        _____ (measurement trust)\n  1169→  Permanence:         P =            _____ (durability)\n  1170→  Total multiplier:   W / C_gross =  _____ (welfare per gross ton)\n  1171→```\n  1172→\n  1173→---\n  1174→\n  1175→## Appendix B: Factor Domain Summary\n  1176→\n  1177→| Factor | Floor | Ceiling | Zero kills? | Baseline offset value | Best-case value |\n  1178→|--------|-------|---------|-------------|----------------------|-----------------|\n  1179→| $C$ | 0 | $+\\infty$ | Yes | Project-dependent | Project-dependent |\n  1180→| $E$ | 0 | 5.0 | Yes | ~1.0 | 4.0-5.0 |\n  1181→| $A$ | 0 | 1.0 | Yes | ~0.3 (top-down) | 1.0 (community-led) |\n  1182→| $B$ | 0.6 | 1.7 | No (floor > 0) | 1.0 (urban green) | 1.7 (mangrove + adj) |\n  1183→| $V$ | 0 | 1.0 | Yes | ~0.5 (satellite only) | 1.0 (full transparency) |\n  1184→| $P$ | 0.2 | 0.95 | Effectively no | 0.50-0.70 | 0.95 (mangrove + tenure) |\n  1185→\n  1186→**Maximum possible multiplier** (excluding $C$):\n  1187→\n  1188→$$E_{max} \\times A_{max} \\times B_{max} \\times V_{max} \\times P_{max} = 5.0 \\times 1.0 \\times 1.7 \\times 1.0 \\times 0.95 = 8.075$$\n  1189→\n  1190→This means a best-in-class project produces up to **8x** its adjusted carbon tonnage in welfare-tons. Combined with the fact that best-in-class projects also have higher $\\alpha_{add}$ (less additionality discount), the effective amplification over a standard offset ranges from **5-10x** as targeted.\n  1191→\n  1192→---\n  1193→\n  1194→*\"Parasparopagraho Jivanam\" -- Souls render service to one another.*\n  1195→\n  1196→*Welfare-tons measure whether we are living up to that.*\n  1197→"}]},"uuid":"83bc9ec8-468c-435d-9b6a-85634c5e86c2","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:21:05.060Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"04a9e506-ba77-4b50-b3c2-27e6858e53d3","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
