{"parentUuid":"1d962fd6-27bc-4bed-b6a2-821654cc12ae","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"3cfdca64-d5a0-407a-b98d-81d58c820453","agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011hZjTpr4Rt9Ls4oMHNeARi","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Ocean Cleanup project AI plastic identification progress 2025 2026 rivers oceans\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"AI system tracks ocean plastic from space to help cleanup efforts • Muser Press\",\"url\":\"https://www.muser.press/2026/03/09/ai-tracks-ocean-plastic-from-space/\"},{\"title\":\"Ocean Plastic Islands: AI & Satellite Data Revolutionize Detection\",\"url\":\"https://www.rinnovabili.net/environment/ocean-plastic-islands-ai-satellite-detection/\"},{\"title\":\"How AWS, The Ocean Cleanup, and artificial intelligence are finding ocean plastic - Amazon Sustainability\",\"url\":\"https://sustainability.aboutamazon.com/stories/how-aws--the-ocean-cleanup--and-artificial-intelligence-are-find\"},{\"title\":\"Japan and The Ocean Cleanup: Harnessing AI and Innovation to Turn the Tide on Plastic Pollution | Updates | The Ocean Cleanup\",\"url\":\"https://theoceancleanup.com/updates/japan-and-the-ocean-cleanup-harnessing-ai-and-innovation-to-turn-the-tide-on-plastic-pollution/\"},{\"title\":\"New AI Project Aims to Detect and Predict Ocean Plastic Drift from Space - Orbital Today\",\"url\":\"https://orbitaltoday.com/2026/03/11/new-ai-project-aims-to-detect-and-predict-ocean-plastic-drift-from-space/\"},{\"title\":\"Using AI to Identify Plastic Pollution and Expedite Ocean Cleanup — Xyonix, AI Consulting & Custom Solutions\",\"url\":\"https://www.xyonix.com/blog/using-ai-to-identify-plastic-pollution-and-expedite-ocean-cleanup\"},{\"title\":\"Researching ocean plastic | The Ocean Cleanup\",\"url\":\"https://theoceancleanup.com/research/\"},{\"title\":\"Using AI to Monitor Plastic Density in the Ocean | Updates | The Ocean Cleanup\",\"url\":\"https://theoceancleanup.com/updates/using-artificial-intelligence-to-monitor-plastic-density-in-the-ocean/\"},{\"title\":\"The Ocean Cleanup and AWS Join Forces to Accelerate Ocean Plastic Removal using AI | Press Release | The Ocean Cleanup\",\"url\":\"https://theoceancleanup.com/press/press-releases/the-ocean-cleanup-and-aws-join-forces/\"},{\"title\":\"AI-powered tech supercharges ocean cleanup, boosting plastic collection by 60%\",\"url\":\"https://phys.org/news/2025-04-ai-powered-tech-supercharges-ocean.html\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's an overview of the Ocean Cleanup project's AI plastic identification progress in 2025-2026:\n\n## Major AI Projects and Developments\n\nThe ADOPT (AI for Detecting Ocean Plastic Pollution with Tracking) project combines two tools: the first analyzes satellite images to identify concentrations of floating debris, while the second predicts how these patches will move using machine learning to refine existing models of winds and ocean currents. The technology has reached the proof-of-concept stage and is ready for field testing.\n\n## AWS Partnership (2025)\n\nIn July 2025, The Ocean Cleanup announced a collaboration with Amazon Web Services to leverage AWS's advanced artificial intelligence, machine learning, and cloud computing capabilities to clean the Great Pacific Garbage Patch and remove 90% of floating ocean plastic by 2040. This initiative will enable The Ocean Cleanup to more effectively identify, track, and predict ocean plastic accumulation, initially focusing on \"hotspot hunting\" capabilities, with AWS providing technologies from IoT, satellite, and edge computing to track plastic accumulation and create a \"plastic navigation\" system.\n\n## River and Ocean Monitoring Systems\n\nThe Automatic Debris Imaging System (ADIS) identifies and classifies plastic \"hotspots\" in real time, and predictive modeling using wind, currents, and river data forecasts where plastics will accumulate. The Ocean Cleanup places cameras on bridges as part of their River Monitoring System, which capture images of plastic debris in rivers that are used to train AI models to identify and categorize plastic pollution.\n\n## Efficiency Improvements\n\nAn AI-driven routing algorithm for plastic-collecting ships increases ocean plastic removal efficiency by over 60% without raising costs, with artificial intelligence-driven algorithms dramatically accelerating plastic waste removal.\n\n## Project Timeline\n\nThe two-year ADOPT project will officially conclude in fall 2026, with researchers expecting to deliver a working proof of concept, two scientific publications, and open-source code for both systems.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"63696712-211f-4cae-9a62-d4725c2fcd67","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:22:00.305Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"1d962fd6-27bc-4bed-b6a2-821654cc12ae","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
