{"parentUuid":"9db6b915-af38-45d7-8a56-78ab6b89cada","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"3cfdca64-d5a0-407a-b98d-81d58c820453","agentId":"adb9276692a3e70f3","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017LFFDTXAFa6FFz895c4os1","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Effective Altruism metrics QALY DALY WELLBY comparison impact measurement limitations 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"To WELLBY or not to WELLBY? Measuring non-health, non-pecuniary benefits using subjective wellbeing — EA Forum\",\"url\":\"https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/posts/dk48Sn6hpbMWeJo4G/to-wellby-or-not-to-wellby-measuring-non-health-non\"},{\"title\":\"Effective Altruism, and building a better QALY – Opentheory.net\",\"url\":\"https://opentheory.net/2015/06/effective-altruism-and-building-a-better-qaly/\"},{\"title\":\"Measuring benefits · Giving What We Can\",\"url\":\"https://www.givingwhatwecan.org/blog/measuring-benefits\"},{\"title\":\"Health and happiness research topics—Part 2: The HALY+: Improving preference-based health metrics — EA Forum\",\"url\":\"https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/posts/z2CjXfttCmHgKwum8/health-and-happiness-research-topics-part-2-the-haly\"},{\"title\":\"Does a DALY approach underrate the badness of mental illness? — EA Forum\",\"url\":\"https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/posts/ebcwjBJqXYhwA8Y4s/does-a-daly-approach-underrate-the-badness-of-mental-illness\"},{\"title\":\"How to quantify global human suffering? Results from OPIS’s pilot survey — EA Forum\",\"url\":\"https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/posts/hTGScBoBDKwmAcGP6/how-to-quantify-global-human-suffering-results-from-opis-s\"},{\"title\":\"Health and happiness research topics—part 1: background on QALYs and DALYs - Rethink Priorities\",\"url\":\"https://rethinkpriorities.org/research-area/health-and-happiness-research-topics-background-on-qalys-and-dalys/\"},{\"title\":\"Measuring Good Better — EA Forum\",\"url\":\"https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/posts/8whqn2GrJfvTjhov6/measuring-good-better-1\"},{\"title\":\"Adjusted life year - EA Forum\",\"url\":\"https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/topics/adjusted-life-year\"},{\"title\":\"Health and happiness research topics—Part 1: Background on QALYs and DALYs — EA Forum\",\"url\":\"https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/posts/Lncdn3tXi2aRt56k5/health-and-happiness-research-topics-part-1-background-on\"}]\n\nBased on my search results, here's a comprehensive overview of Effective Altruism metrics, including QALY, DALY, and WELLBY, along with their limitations and comparison for impact measurement:\n\n## Overview of Key Metrics\n\nHealth-Adjusted Life Years (HALYs) involve the trade-off between duration and quality of health in a single numerical unit, with two main types: Quality-Adjusted Life Years (QALYs) and Disability-Adjusted Life Years (DALYs). QALYs have been used in the assessment of health interventions for three decades as an aid to resource allocation.\n\nWellbeing-adjusted life years (WALYs or WELLBYs) adjust based on measures of wellbeing, such as hedonic experience or preference satisfaction. One WELLBY is a one-point increase on a 0-10 life satisfaction scale for one year.\n\n## Key Differences and Advantages\n\nUsing WELLBYs can change funding priorities by giving more weight to improving mental health, compared to DALYs or income measures. Within the effective altruism community, WALYs are generally preferred over HALYs, because things other than health can contribute to a person's wellbeing, and because health itself, while often a good proxy for wellbeing, is not generally regarded as intrinsically valuable.\n\n## Significant Limitations\n\n### DALYs and QALYs\n\nThe limitations of QALYs and DALYs are well-established and there has been a long-standing call for something better and broader than Q/DALYs. Five problems with them include: they neglect non-health consequences of health interventions, rely on poorly-informed judgements of the general public, and fail to acknowledge extreme suffering (and happiness).\n\nDALYs are exposed to bias stemming from affective forecasting problems and a reliance on healthy people's views as to which states are more healthy than others.\n\n### WELLBYs\n\nLike HALYs, life satisfaction and the WELLBY do not capture extreme positive or negative states, since scores are bounded by 0 and 10, and it is possible that the full toll of severe pain, depression and psychosis simply cannot be measured by the WELLBY, QALY or DALY.\n\nExisting wellbeing metrics, including the DALY and measures of improved life satisfaction such as the WELLBY, do not directly measure suffering – a key determinant of wellbeing.\n\n## Recent Developments\n\nA survey carried out from September 2024 to March 2025 gathered both momentary measures of wellbeing and retrospective estimates of the duration of suffering at different intensity ranges for over 110 diseases, conditions and experiences.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"6498f292-3d1e-4c0f-a601-05cddf5e333b","timestamp":"2026-03-15T14:22:02.003Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"9db6b915-af38-45d7-8a56-78ab6b89cada","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
